elly]] in 1826, Simpson becomes governor of the Canadian region.<ref>{{cite web |title=Our History: People: Governors: Sir John Henry Pelly, Bart. |website=HBC Heritage |url=http://hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/people/governors/johnhenrypelly |access-date=7 October 2015}}</ref>\n# 1852\u201356&nbsp; [[Andrew Wedderburn Colvile]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Colville, Andrew |website=Hudson's Bay Company Archives |url=https://www.gov.mb.ca/chc/archives/hbca/biographical/c/colville_andrew.pdf |access-date=6 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518103527/https://www.gov.mb.ca/chc/archives/hbca/biographical/c/colville_andrew.pdf |archivedate=18 May 2015  }}</ref>\n# 1856\u201358&nbsp; [[John Shepherd (governor and chairman)|John Shepherd]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Shepherd, John |website=Hudson's Bay Company Archives |url=https://www.gov.mb.ca/chc/archives/hbca/biographical/s/shepherd_john.pdf |access-date=7 October 2015}}</ref>\n# 1858\u201363&nbsp; [[Henry Hulse Berens]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Berens, Henry Hulse |website=Hudson's Bay Company Archives |url=https://www.gov.mb.ca/chc/archives/hbca/biographical/b/berens_henry.pdf |access-date=7 October 2015}}</ref>\n# 1863\u201368&nbsp; Sir [[Sir Edmund Walker Head, 8th Baronet|Edmund Walker Head]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Head, Edmund Walker |website=Hudson's Bay Company Archives |url=https://www.gov.mb.ca/chc/archives/hbca/biographical/h/head_edmund-walker.pdf |access-date=7 October 2015}}</ref>\n# 1868\u201369&nbsp; [[John Wodehouse, 1st Earl of Kimberley]]\n# 1869\u201374&nbsp; Sir [[Stafford Northcote, 1st Earl of Iddesleigh|Stafford Henry Northcote]]<ref>{{cite DNB |wstitle=Northcote, Stafford Henry |last=Sanders |first=Lloyd Charles |authorlink=Lloyd Charles Sanders |volume=41 |pages=194\u2013199}}</ref>\n# 1874\u201380&nbsp; [[George Goschen, 1st Viscount Goschen|George Joachim Goschen]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Goschen, George Joachim |website=Hudson's Bay Company Archives |url=https://www.gov.mb.ca/chc/archives/hbca/biographical/g/goschen_george-joachim.pdf |access-date=7 October 2015}}</ref>\n# 1880\u201389&nbsp; [[Eden Colvile]]<ref>{{cite DCB |title=Colvile, Eden |first=J.E. |last=Rea |volume=12 |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/colvile_eden_12E.html |access-date=9 October 2015}}</ref>\n# 1889\u20131914&nbsp; [[Donald Smith, 1st Baron Strathcona and Mount Royal|Donald Alexander Smith]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our History: People: Governors: Donald A. Smith |website=HBC Heritage |url=http://hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/people/governors/donaldsmith |access-date=7 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928171433/http://www.hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/people/governors/donaldsmith |archivedate=28 September 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Smith, Donald Alexander |website=Hudson's Bay Company Archives |url=https://www.gov.mb.ca/chc/archives/hbca/biographical/s/smith_donald-alexander.pdf |access-date=7 October 2015}}</ref>\n# 1914\u201315&nbsp; Sir Thomas Skinner<ref>{{cite web |title=Skinner, Thomas |website=Hudson's Bay Company Archives |url=https://www.gov.mb.ca/chc/archives/hbca/biographical/s/skinner_thomas1914-1915.pdf |access-date=7 October 2015}}</ref>\n# 1916\u201325&nbsp; [[Robert Kindersley, 1st Baron Kindersley|Sir Robert Molesworth Kindersley]]\n# 1925\u201331&nbsp; Charles Vincent Sale\n# 1931\u201352&nbsp; Sir [[Patrick Ashley Cooper]] \u2013 first governor to visit HBC operations in Canada.<ref>{{cite book |last=Newman |first=Peter C. |title=Here Be Dragons: Telling Tales of People, Passion and Power |location=Toronto |publisher=McClelland & Stewart |date=2004 |url={{google books||plainurl=yes|page=591}} |p=591 |isbn=978-0-7710-6792-1 |access-date=9 October 2015}}</ref>\n# 1952\u201365&nbsp; [[Tony Keswick|William \"Tony\" Keswick]]\n# 1965\u201370&nbsp; [[Derick Heathcoat-Amory, 1st Viscount Amory|Derick Heathcoat-Amory]]\n# 1970\u201382&nbsp; George T. Richardson\n# 1982\u201394&nbsp; Donald S. McGiverin\n# 1994\u201397&nbsp; David E. Mitchell\n# 1997\u20132006&nbsp; [[Yves Fortier (lawyer)|L. Yves Fortier]]\n# 2006\u201308&nbsp; [[Jerry Zucker (businessman)|Jerry Zucker]]\n# 2008&nbsp; [[Anita Zucker]] \u2013 first female governor.\n# 2008\u2013present&nbsp; [[Richard A. Baker (businessman)|Richard Baker]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Miscellany==\n===Rent obligation under charter===\nUnder the charter establishing Hudson's Bay Company, the company was required to give two [[elk]] skins and two black [[beaver]] pelts to the English king, then Charles II, or his heirs, whenever the monarch visited Rupert's Land. The exact text from the 1670 Charter reads:{{quote|...Yielding and paying yearly to us and our heirs and successors for the same two Elks and two Black beavers whensoever and as often as We, our heirs and successors shall happen to enter into the said Countries, Territories and Regions hereby granted.<ref name=charter/>}}\n\nThe ceremony was first conducted with the [[Prince of Wales]] (the future Edward VIII) in 1927, then with King [[George VI]] in 1939, and last with his daughter, Queen [[Elizabeth II]] in 1959 and 1970. On the last such visit, the pelts were given in the form of two live beavers, which the Queen donated to the Winnipeg Zoo in [[Assiniboine Park]]. However, when the company permanently moved its headquarters to Canada, the Charter was amended to remove the rent obligation. Each of the four \"rent ceremonies\" took place in or around Winnipeg.<ref>{{cite web |title=Our History: Business: Fur Trade: The Rent Ceremony |website=HBC Heritage |url=http://www.hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/business/fur/rentceremony |access-date=6 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===HBC explorers, builders, and associates===\n* [[James Knight (explorer)|James Knight]] (c. 1640 \u2013 c. 1721) was a director of Hudson's Bay Company and an explorer who died in an expedition to the Northwest Passage.<ref>{{cite DCB |title=Knight, James |first=Ernest S. |last=Dodge |volume=2 |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/knight_james_2E.html |accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Our History: People: Associates: James Knight |website=HBC Heritage |url=http://hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/people/associates/knight |access-date=7 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite DNB |wstitle=Knight, James |last=Laughton |first=John Knox |authorlink=John Knox Laughton |volume=31 |page=254}}</ref>\n* [[Henry Kelsey]] (c. 1667 \u2013 1 November 1724), a.k.a. the Boy Kelsey, was an English fur trader, explorer, and sailor who played an important role in establishing Hudson's Bay Company in Canada. In 1690, Henry Kelsey embarked on a 2-year exploration journey that made him the first white man to see buffalo.<ref>{{cite DCB |title=Kelsey, Henry |volume=2 |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/kelsey_henry_2E.html |access-date=7 October 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Thanadelthur]] (c. 1697 \u2013 5 February 1717) was a woman of the Chipewyan nation who served as a guide and interpreter for Hudson's Bay Company.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our History: People: Women: Thanadelthur |website=HBC Heritage |url=http://hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/people/women/thanadelthur.asp |access-date=7 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222105152/http://hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/people/women/thanadelthur.asp |archivedate=22 December 2015 }}</ref>\n* [[Samuel Hearne]] (1745\u201392) was an English explorer, fur-trader, author, and naturalist. In 1774, Hearne built Cumberland House for the Hudson's Bay Company, its first interior trading post and the first permanent settlement in present Saskatchewan.<ref name=DNB_Hearne/><ref name=Hearne/>\n* [[David Thompson (explorer)|David Thompson]] (30 April 1770 \u2013 10 February 1857) was a British-Canadian fur trader that worked for both the Hudson's Bay Company and the North West Trading Company. He is best known for his extensive explorations and map-making activities. He mapped almost half of North America between the 46th and 60th parallels, from the St.Lawrence and Great Lakes all the way to the Pacific.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our History: People: Explorers: David Thompson |website=HBC Heritage |url=http://hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/people/explorers/david-thompson |access-date=7 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007053041/http://hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/people/explorers/david-thompson |archivedate= 7 October 2015 }}</ref>\n* [[Thomas Douglas, 5th Earl of Selkirk|Thomas Douglas, Lord Selkirk]] (20 June 1771 \u2013 8 April 1820) was a Scottish peer. He was a Scottish philanthropist who, as HBC's majority shareholder, arranged to purchase land at Red River to establish a colony for dispossessed Scottish immigrants.<ref>{{cite DNB |wstitle=Douglas, Thomas (1771-1820) |last=Christy |first=Miller |authorlink=Miller Christy |volume=15 |pages=350\u2013353}}</ref>\n* [[Isobel Gunn]] or Isabella Gunn (c. 1780 \u2013 7 November 1861), also known as John Fubbister or Mary Fubbister, was a Scottish labourer employed by Hudson's Bay Company (HBC), noted for having passed herself as a man, thereby becoming the first European woman to travel to Rupert's Land, now part of Western Canada.<ref>{{cite web |title=Our History: People: Women: Isobel Gunn |website=HBC Heritage |url=http://hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/people/women/isobelgunn.asp |access-date=7 October 2015}}</ref>\n* [[George Simpson (administrator)|George Simpson]] (1787 \u2013 7 September 1860) was the Canadian governor of Hudson's Bay Company during the period of its greatest power, a period which began in 1821 following the company's merger with the North West Trading Company.<ref>{{cite DNB |wstitle=Simpson, George |last=Harris |first=Charles Alexander |authorlink=Charles Alexander Harris |volume=52 |pages=269\u2013270}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Our History: People: Builders: Sir George Simpson |website=HBC Heritage |url=http://hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/people/builders/simpson.asp |access-date=7 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222114551/http://hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/people/builders/simpson.asp |archivedate=22 December 2015 }}</ref>\n* [[John McLean (explorer)|John McLean]] (c. 1799{{nbsp}}\u2013 8 September 1890), a Scoto-Canadian trapper and trader who successfully crossed the entire [[Labrador Peninsula]], opening up an overland route between [[Fort Smith, Labrador|Fort Smith]] on [[Lake Melville]] and [[Fort Chimo]] on [[Ungava Bay]]; first European to discover [[Churchill Falls]] on the [[Churchill River (Atlantic)|Churchill River]].<ref>{{citation |last=Wells |first=Garron |contribution=John McLean |contribution-url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/mclean_john_1890_11E.html |title=Dictionary of Canadian Biography |url=http://www.biographi.ca |volume=Vol. XI |publisher=University of Toronto |location=Toronto |date=1982 }}.</ref>\n* [[Donald Smith, 1st Baron Strathcona and Mount Royal]] (6 August 1820 \u2013 21 January 1914), at various times Chief Factor of the [[Labrador]] district, Commissioner of the Montreal district, and President of the Council of the Northern Department, who pacified [[Louis Riel]] during the [[Red River Rebellion]] of 1870, thus enabling the transfer of [[Rupert's Land]] from the HBC to the fledgling government of Canada. Later, he became Governor of the HBC.<ref name=\"martin\">{{cite journal|last1=Martin|first1=Joseph E.|title=Titans|journal=Canada's History|year=2017|volume=97|issue=5|pages=47\u201353|issn=1920-9894}}</ref>\n* [[John Rae (explorer)|Dr. John Rae]] (Inuktitut\u2002Aglooka\u2002\u140a\u14a1\u14d8\u1472\u2002English: \"long strider\") (30 September 1813 \u2013 22 July 1893) was a Scottish doctor who explored Northern Canada, surveyed parts of the Northwest Passage and reported the fate of the Franklin Expedition.<ref>{{cite DNB |wstitle=Rae, John |last=Rix |first=Herbert |authorlink=Herbert Rix |volume=47 |pages=151\u2013153}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Our History: People: Explorers: Dr. John Rae |website=HBC Heritage |url=http://hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/people/explorers/johnrae.asp |access-date=7 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151009114937/http://hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/people/explorers/johnrae.asp |archivedate= 9 October 2015 }}</ref>\n* [[William Keswick]] (15 April 1834 \u2013 9 March 1912) and grandson [[Keswick family#Sir William Johnstone \"Tony\" Keswick (1903\u20131990)|Sir William Johnstone Keswick]] (1903\u201390) served at HBC; the former as a director and later as governor from 1952 to 1965. The Keswick family are the Scottish business dynasty that controls [[Hong Kong]]-based [[Jardine Matheson]], one of the original British trading houses or Hongs in [[British Hong Kong]].\n\n===HBC sternwheelers and steamships===\n* ''[[Beaver (steamship)|Beaver]]'' (1835\u201374)\n* ''Otter'' (1852\u201395)<ref>{{cite book|last=Hacking, Lamb|first=Norman R., W. Kaye|title=The Princess Story: A Century and A Half of West Coast Shipping|year=1976|publisher=Mitchell Press Ltd|location=Vancouver}}</ref>\n* ''[[Anson Northup]]'' (1859\u201360)<ref>{{cite book|last=Watson|first=Robert|title=The Anson Northup, First Steamboat on the Red River|year=March 1928|publisher=The Beaver|pages=162, 163}}</ref>\n* ''Caledonia'' (1891\u201398) \u2013 She ran aground on rocks at Port Simpson during a storm and her hull was destroyed. Her engines were put into the ''Caledonia 2''\n* ''Caledonia (2)'' (1898\u20131909) \u2013 Her machinery was from the ''Caledonia 1''\n* ''[[Mount Royal (sternwheeler)|Mount Royal]]'' (1902\u201307)\n* ''[[Princess Louise (sidewheeler)|Princess Louise]]'' (1878\u201383)\n* ''[[Strathcona (sternwheeler)|Strathcona]]'' (1900)\n* ''Port Simpson'' (1907\u201312)\n* ''[[Hazelton (sternwheeler)|Hazelton]]'' (1907\u201312)\n* ''Distributor'' (1920\u201348)<ref>{{cite book|title=The Beaver|year=June 1925|page=121}}</ref>\n\n===Rivals===\nThe HBC is the only European trading company to have survived and outlived all its rivals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://smbp.uwaterloo.ca/2016/06/hbc-supply-chain-department-at-n-a-s-oldest-firm-is-a-modern-day-leader/ |title=HBC: Supply Chain Department at N.A.'s Oldest Firm is a Modern Day Leader |first=Russ |last=Horner |date=23 June 2016 |work=Social Media for Business Performance |publisher=University of Waterloo Centre for Extended Learning}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Years !! Company !! Fate\n|-\n| 1551\u20131917 || [[Muscovy Company]] || Taken over by the [[Soviet Union]] and now operates as charity.\n|-\n| 1581\u20131825 || [[Levant Company]] || Dissolved\n|-\n| 1600\u20131874 || {{nowrap|[[East India Company|Honourable East India Company]]}} || Dissolved\n|-\n| 1602\u20131800 || [[Dutch East India Company]] || Went bankrupt and assets taken over by Dutch government\n|-\n| 1621\u20131791 || [[Dutch West India Company]] || Bought by the Dutch government\n|-\n| 1672\u20131752 || [[Royal African Company]] || Replaced by the [[African Company of Merchants]], which folded in 1821.\n|-\n| {{nowrap|1711\u20131850s}} || [[South Sea Company]] || Abolished by bankruptcy and the [[Louisiana Purchase]]\n|-\n| 1779\u20131821 || [[North West Company]] || Merged with the HBC\n|-\n| 1799\u20131867 || [[Russian-American Company]] || Folded with the sale of [[Russian America]] to the U.S. and commercial assets in North America sold to Hutchinson, Kohl & Company (now as the [[Alaska Commercial Company]])\n|-\n| 1808\u20131842 || [[American Fur Company]] || Folded\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}<!-- Please respect alphabetical order -->\n* [[Beaver hat]]\n* [[British colonization of the Americas]]\n* [[Frontier (2016 TV series)|''Frontier'' (2016 TV series)]]\n* [[Home Outfitters]]\n* [[Hudson's Bay tokens]]\n* [[James Douglas (governor)]]\n* [[List of department stores by country#Canada|List of department stores by country \u00a7 Canada]]\n* [[List of Hudson's Bay Company brands]]\n* [[List of Hudson's Bay Company trading posts]]\n* [[List of trading companies]]\n* [[New Caledonia (Canada)]]\n* [[North-West Rebellion]]\n* {{lang|fr|[[Voyageurs]]}}\n{{div col end}}\n{{Portal inline|Canada}} {{Portal inline|Companies}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Bryce |first=George |authorlink=George Bryce |url={{google books|Imc5lXU3KrkC|plainurl=yes}} |title=The Remarkable History of Hudson's Bay Company |location=New York |publisher=B. Franklin |date=1968}}\n* {{citation |last=Buss |first=Helen M |year=2003 |title=Undelivered Letters to Hudson's Bay Company Men on the Northwest Coast |url={{google books|N4QKXOOjv_cC|plainurl=yes}} |publisher=University of British Columbia Press |isbn=978-0-7748-0973-3 }}\n* {{cite journal | journal= Periodical. An Illustrated Canadian History Magazine Published by the HBC 1920 \u2013 1994. By CNHS Since 1994 | title=The Beaver: Exploring Canada's History | place= Winnipeg |year= 1920 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Cowie |first=Isaac |authorlink=Isaac Cowie |title=The Company of Adventurers: a Narrative of Seven Years in the Service of the Hudson's Bay Company during 1867\u20131874, on the Great Buffalo Plains |location=Toronto |publisher=William Briggs |date=1913 |url=https://archive.org/details/companyofadventu00cowiuoft}}\n* {{cite book |last=Dillon |first=Richard H. |title=Siskiyou Trail: Hudson's Bay Company Route to California |location=New York |publisher=McGraw-Hill |date=2012 |orig-year=1975 |isbn=978-1-6180-9063-8}}\n* {{citation |last=Elle |first=Andra-Warner |year=2009 |title=Hudson's Bay Company Adventures: The Rollicking Saga of Canada's Fur Traders |url={{google books|3iXIqHDnIs4C|plainurl=yes}} |publisher=Heritage House |isbn=978-1-894974-68-4 }}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Gibson |editor1-first=James R.|date=2019|title=\u201cOpposition on the Coa