ruce. M. |title=The Woman who Married a Beaver: Trade Patterns and Gender Roles in the Ojibwa Fur Trade |journal=Ethnohistory |volume=46 |issue=1 |pages=109\u2013147 |date=Winter 1999 |jstor=483430 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Willson |first=Beckles |authorlink=Henry Beckles Willson| title=The Great Company (1667\u20131871): A History of the Honourable Company of Merchants-adventurers Trading Into Hudson's Bay |location=London |publisher=Smith, Elder and Company |date=1900 |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/42279/42279-h/42279-h.htm}} \u2013 Also: {{google books|HwsqAAAAYAAJ|The Great Company, 1667\u20131871: Being a History of the Honourable Company of Merchants-Adventurers Trading into Hudson's Bay }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{EB9 Poster}}\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Hudson's Bay Company}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/home HBC Heritage website]\n* [https://www.gov.mb.ca/chc/archives/hbca/index.html Hudson's Bay Company Archives \u2013 held by the Government of Manitoba]\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=Hudson's+Bay+Company | name=Hudson's Bay Company}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |search=( \"Hudson's Bay Company\" )}}\n* [http://digital.lib.washington.edu/findingaids/view?docId=WorkJohn4981.xml John Work Papers.] 1823\u201362. 0.42 cubic feet (1 box). At the [http://lib.washington.edu/specialcollections/laws Labor Archives of Washington, University of Washington Libraries Special Collections.] Contains records from Work's service as an officer of the Hudson's Bay Company at various company settlements, including Fort Vancouver, Fort Colvile, Spokane House, Fort Simpson, Fort Nisqually, and Fort Victoria.\n* [http://nwda-db.wsulibs.wsu.edu/findaid/ark:/80444/xv58833 Hudson's Bay Company papers at the University of Oregon]\n* [http://www.nfb.ca/film/other_side_of_the_ledger/ ''The Other Side of the Ledger: An Indian View of the Hudson's Bay Company'']\n* [http://thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/hudsons-bay-company The Canadian Encyclopedia, The Hudson's Bay Company]\n* [http://digitalcollections.library.ubc.ca/cdm/landingpage/collection/bullock H. Bullock-Webster fonds] \u2013 An artistic rendition of the Canadian fur trade, from the UBC Library Digital Collections, depicting social life, activities and customs in Hudson's Bay Company posts in the 19th Century\n* [https://archives-manuscripts.dartmouth.edu/repositories/2/resources/1105 Elizabeth F. Washburn Journal on her experiences on board the Hudson's Bay Company's supply ship \"Rupertsland\"] at Dartmouth College Library\n* {{PM20|FID=co/059846|TEXT=Documents and clippings about|NAME=}}\n\n{{Hudson's Bay Trading_Company, L.P.}}\n{{Chartered companies}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hudson's Bay Company| ]]\n[[Category:1670 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:2008 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:2012 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:2020 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:British colonization of the Americas]]\n[[Category:Canadian brands]]\n[[Category:Canadian folklore]]\n[[Category:Chartered companies]]\n[[Category:Clothing retailers of Canada]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Brampton]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1670]]\n[[Category:Companies formerly listed on the Toronto Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Economic history of Canada]]\n[[Category:English colonization of the Americas]]\n[[Category:Fur trade]]\n[[Category:History of the Pacific Northwest]]\n[[Category:History of the Rocky Mountains]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in Canada]]\n[[Category:Oregon Country]]\n[[Category:Private equity portfolio companies]]\n[[Category:Trading companies]]\n", "name_user": "2604:3d09:ad82:a900:a9f4:cdec:ecf:d17c", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hudson%27s_Bay_Company"}
{"title_page": "Ana Miranda Paz", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = \n| name               = Ana Miranda Paz\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| honorific-suffix   = \n| image              = File:Ana Miranda 2014.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| order              = \n| office             = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n| term_start         = 1 January 2012\n| term_end           = 9 July 2013\n| alongside          = \n| term_start2        =  28 February 2018\n| term_end2          =  2020\n| constituency       = [[Spain (European Parliament constituency)|Spain]]\n| constituency2       = Spain\n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| majority           = \n| prior_term         =\n| birth_date         = {{birth-date and age|2 May 1971}}\n| birth_place        = [[Cuntis]], [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], [[Spain]]\n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        = \n| nationality        = [[Spanish people|Spanish]] \n| party              = [[Galician Nationalist Bloc]]\n| otherparty         = [[Europe of the Peoples\u2013Greens]], [[The Peoples Decide]]\n| spouse             = \n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| residence          = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Santiago de Compostela]]\n| occupation         = Politician\n| profession         = \n| known_for          = \n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| religion           = \n| awards             =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Ana Maria Miranda Paz''' is a Spanish politician of the [[Galician Nationalist Bloc]]. She has served twice in the  [[European Parliament]].\n\n==Career in the European Parliament==\nMiranda was on the list of the [[Europe of the Peoples\u2013Greens]] electoral alliance in the [[2009 European Parliament election|2009 European elections]]. The alliance won a single seat which was held first by [[Oriol Junqueras]] ([[Republican Left of Catalonia]]). Miranda joined the European Parliament in January 2012 after Junqueras stood down.  She served until 2013.<ref name=\"EP\">[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/24942/ANA+MARIA_MIRANDA+PAZ_home.html Ana Maria Miranda Paz]. European Parliament.</ref><ref name=\"EurP\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.europapress.es/galicia/noticia-ana-miranda-bng-sustituira-domingo-junqueras-erc-escano-parlamento-europeo-20111231131822.html |title=Ana Miranda (BNG) sustituir\u00e1 este domingo a Junqueras (ERC) en su esca\u00f1o en el Parlamento |date=31 December 2011 |work=Europa Press |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n[[Image:Mobilizaci\u00f3n_BNG_Europeas_2014-Vence_Miranda_e_Nogueira_-Praza_Publica.jpg|thumb|right|Ana Miranda with [[Camilo Nogueira]] and Xavier Vence in the 2014 European elections campaign.]]\nIn the [[2014 European Parliament election|2014 European elections]], she stood on the list of [[The Peoples Decide]] alliance. The alliance won a single seat which it was decided to allocate on a rotative basis to Ana Miranda and Josu Juaristi. The latter candidate, a member of [[EH Bildu]], held the seat first.\nMiranda took over the seat in February 2018, joining the parliamentary group of the [[Greens/European Free Alliance]] in March.<ref name=\"EP\" /> \nIn the 2019 election the Galicians nationalists were allied with the electoral coalition [[Ahora Rep\u00fablicas]], which included ERC, EH Bildu and some other minor nationalist parties as well. The coalition obtained 3 seats, which will be held rotatively, with Ana Miranda set to hold a seat for the last 3.5 years of the Parliament.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ana Miranda (politician)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miranda Paz, Ana}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:MEPs for Spain 2009\u20132014]]\n[[Category:MEPs for Spain 2014\u20132019]]\n[[Category:People from Caldas (comarca)]]\n[[Category:Galician Nationalist Bloc MEPs]]\n[[Category:Europe of the Peoples\u2013Greens MEPs]]\n[[Category:Women MEPs for Spain]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish women politicians]]\n\n\n{{Spain-MEP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = \n| name               = Ana Miranda Paz\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| honorific-suffix   = \n| image              = File:Ana Miranda 2014.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| order              = \n| office             = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n| term_start         = 1 January 2012\n| term_end           = 9 July 2013\n| alongside          = \n| term_start2        =  28 February 2018\n| term_end2          =  2020\n| constituency       = [[Spain (European Parliament constituency)|Spain]]\n| constituency2       = Spain\n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| majority           = \n| prior_term         =\n| birth_date         = {{birth-date and age|2 May 1971}}\n| birth_place        = [[Cuntis]], [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], [[Spain]]\n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        = \n| nationality        = [[Spanish people|Spanish]] \n| party              = [[Galician Nationalist Bloc]]\n| otherparty         = [[Europe of the Peoples\u2013Greens]], [[The Peoples Decide]]\n| spouse             = \n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| residence          = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater    