{"title_page": "USS Paul Ignatius", "text_new": "{{Use American English}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= USS Paul Ignatius (DDG-117) prepares to moor at Naval Station Mayport on 31 July 2019 - 2.jpg\n|Ship caption= USS Paul Ignatius (DDG-117) at Naval Station Mayport\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Ship flag={{USN flag}}\n|Ship name=USS ''Paul Ignatius''\n|Ship namesake= [[Paul Ignatius]]<ref name=\"NNS Announcement\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=74367|title=Navy Names Next Two Destroyers|publisher=United States Navy|id=NNS130523-13|date=23 May 2013|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder= [[Ingalls Shipbuilding]]\n|Ship laid down=20 October 2015<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://newsroom.huntingtoningalls.com/releases/ingalls-authenticates-keel-paul-ignatius|title=Ingalls Shipbuilding Authenticates the Keel of Paul Ignatius (DDG 117)|publisher=[[Huntington Ingalls Industries]]|date=20 October 2015|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref>\n|Ship launched=12 November 2016<ref name=\"ddg-117lau\">{{cite press release|url=http://newsroom.huntingtoningalls.com/releases/destroyer-paul-ignatius-ddg-117-launch|title=Huntington Ingalls Industries Launches Arleigh Burke-Class Destroyer Paul Ignatius (DDG 117)|publisher=Huntington Ingalls Industries|date=16 November 2016|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref>\n|Ship sponsor=Nancy W. Ignatius\n|Ship christened=8 April 2017<ref name=\"ddg-117chr\">{{cite press release|url=http://newsroom.huntingtoningalls.com/releases/photo-release-huntington-ingalls-industries-christens-destroyer-paul-ignatius-ddg-117|title=Huntington Ingalls Industries Christens Destroyer Paul Ignatius (DDG 117)|publisher=Huntington Ingalls Industries|date=8 April 2017|accessdate=8 April 2017}}</ref>\n|Ship acquired=22 February 2019<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=108671|title=Navy Accepts Delivery of Future USS Paul Ignatius|publisher=United States Navy|id=NNS190225-07|date=25 February 2019|accessdate=25 February 2019}}</ref>\n|Ship commissioned=27 July 2019<ref name=\"Navy 110375\">{{cite press release|url=https://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=110375|title=Warship USS Paul Ignatius (DDG 117) Brought to Life|publisher=United States Navy|id=NNS190729-10|date=29 July 2019|accessdate=29 July 2019}}</ref>\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=Active, in commission\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship motto=''Always ready, fight on''\n|Ship badge =[[File:USS Paul Ignatius DDG-117 Crest.png|125px|center]]\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Arleigh Burke|destroyer}}, Flight IIA\n|Ship displacement={{convert|9200|LT|abbr=on}}\n|Ship length={{convert|510|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|33|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=4 \u00d7 [[General Electric LM2500|General Electric LM2500-30]] [[gas turbine]]s, 2 shafts, {{convert|100000|shp|MW|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=380 officers and enlisted\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*1 \u00d7 32 cell, 1 \u00d7 64 cell Mk 41 [[vertical launch system]]s, 96 \u00d7 [[RIM-66 Standard|RIM-66 SM-2]], [[BGM-109 Tomahawk]] or [[RUM-139 VL-Asroc]], missiles\n*1 \u00d7 [[5\"/54 caliber Mark 45 gun|{{convert|5|in|mm|abbr=on}}/62]] , 2 \u00d7 [[M242 Bushmaster#Naval|25 mm Mk 38]], 4 \u00d7 [[M2 Browning|.50 cal (12.7 mm)]] guns\n*2 \u00d7 [[Mark 46 torpedo|Mk 46]] triple [[torpedo tube]]s\n*1 \u00d7 20mm [[Phalanx CIWS]]\n|Ship aircraft=2 \u00d7 [[SH-60 Sea Hawk]] helicopters\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''USS ''Paul Ignatius'' (DDG-117)''' is an {{sclass-|Arleigh Burke|destroyer}} of the [[United States Navy]]. She is named for [[Paul Ignatius]] who served as United States [[Secretary of the Navy]] under President [[Lyndon Johnson]] from 1967 to 1969.  Ignatius had previously served as a commissioned lieutenant in the Navy during World War II.  ''Paul Ignatius'' is the 2nd of 8 planned Flight IIA \"technology insertion\" ships, which contains elements of the Flight III ships. \n\nShe was launched on 12 November 2016,<ref name=\"ddg-117lau\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://navaltoday.com/2016/11/16/hii-launches-future-arleigh-burke-destroyer-uss-paul-ignatius/ |title=HII launches future Arleigh Burke destroyer USS Paul Ignatius|publisher=Naval Today|date=16 November 2016|accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref> and was christened on 8 April 2017.<ref name=\"ddg-117chr\"/> The ship was commissioned on 27 July 2019 [[Port Everglades]] in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]]. Dr. Elisa Ignatius, granddaughter to the late Mrs. Nancy Ignatius, will serve as the ship sponsor representative. <ref name=\"Navy 110375\"/><ref>https://www.defense.gov/Newsroom/Releases/Release/Article/1915641/navy-to-commission-guided-missile-destroyer-paul-ignatius/</ref> USS ''Paul Ignatius'' is homeported in [[Mayport, Florida]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Arleigh Burke class destroyer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paul Ignatius (DDG-117)}}\n[[Category:Proposed ships of the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Arleigh Burke-class destroyers]]\n\n\n{{US-mil-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= USS Paul Ignatius (DDG-117) prepares to moor at Naval Station Mayport on 31 July 2019 - 2.jpg\n|Ship caption= USS Paul Ignatius (DDG-117) at Naval Station Mayport\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Ship flag={{USN flag}}\n|Ship name=USS ''Paul Ignatius''\n|Ship namesake= [[Paul Ignatius]]<ref name=\"NNS Announcement\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=74367|title=Navy Names Next Two Destroyers|publisher=United States Navy|id=NNS130523-13|date=23 May 2013|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder= [[Ingalls Shipbuilding]]\n|Ship laid down=20 October 2015<ref>{{cite press r