cement={{convert|9200|LT|abbr=on}}\n|Ship length={{convert|510|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|33|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=4 \u00d7 [[General Electric LM2500|General Electric LM2500-30]] [[gas turbine]]s, 2 shafts, {{convert|100000|shp|MW|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=380 officers and enlisted\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*1 \u00d7 32 cell, 1 \u00d7 64 cell Mk 41 [[vertical launch system]]s, 96 \u00d7 [[RIM-66 Standard|RIM-66 SM-2]], [[BGM-109 Tomahawk]] or [[RUM-139 VL-Asroc]], missiles\n*1 \u00d7 [[5\"/54 caliber Mark 45 gun|{{convert|5|in|mm|abbr=on}}/62]] , 2 \u00d7 [[M242 Bushmaster#Naval|25 mm Mk 38]], 4 \u00d7 [[M2 Browning|.50 cal (12.7 mm)]] guns\n*2 \u00d7 [[Mark 46 torpedo|Mk 46]] triple [[torpedo tube]]s\n*1 \u00d7 20mm [[Phalanx CIWS]]\n|Ship aircraft=2 \u00d7 [[SH-60 Sea Hawk]] helicopters\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''USS ''Paul Ignatius'' (DDG-117)''' is an {{sclass-|Arleigh Burke|destroyer}} of the [[United States Navy]]. She is named for [[Paul Ignatius]] who served as United States [[Secretary of the Navy]] under President [[Lyndon Johnson]] from 1967 to 1969.  Ignatius had previously served as a commissioned lieutenant in the Navy during World War II.  ''Paul Ignatius'' is the 2nd of 8 planned Flight IIA \"technology insertion\" ships, which contains elements of the Flight III ships. \n\nShe was launched on November 12, 2016,<ref name=\"ddg-117lau\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://navaltoday.com/2016/11/16/hii-launches-future-arleigh-burke-destroyer-uss-paul-ignatius/ |title=HII launches future Arleigh Burke destroyer USS Paul Ignatius|publisher=Naval Today|date=16 November 2016|accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref> and was christened on 8 April 2017.<ref name=\"ddg-117chr\"/> The ship was commissioned on 27 July 2019 [[Port Everglades]] in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]]. Dr. Elisa Ignatius, granddaughter to the late Mrs. Nancy Ignatius, will serve as the ship sponsor representative. <ref name=\"Navy 110375\"/><ref>https://www.defense.gov/Newsroom/Releases/Release/Article/1915641/navy-to-commission-guided-missile-destroyer-paul-ignatius/</ref> USS ''Paul Ignatius'' is homeported in [[Mayport, Florida]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Arleigh Burke class destroyer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paul Ignatius (DDG-117)}}\n[[Category:Proposed ships of the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Arleigh Burke-class destroyers]]\n\n\n{{US-mil-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dl2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "en-US;WP:MILFORMAT; tidy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USS_Paul_Ignatius"}
{"title_page": "Tornado outbreak of December 16\u201317, 2019", "text_new": "{{Infobox storm\n| name = Tornado outbreak of December 16\u201317, 2019\n| highest winds = {{convert|158|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}\n| enhanced = yes\n| current advisories = \n| affected = [[Louisiana]], [[Mississippi]], [[Alabama]], [[Tennessee]], [[Florida]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| total fatalities = 3 (+1 non-tornadic) fatalities<ref name=WSB>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsbtv.com/news/trending/deep-south-tornadoes-3-killed-alabama-louisiana-storms-slam-region-officials-say/CERA4K3FHRBPHETEWDRPH2FBK4/|title=Southeast tornadoes: 4 killed in Alabama, Louisiana and Kentucky after storms slam region|last=|first=|date=December 17, 2019|website=WSB-TV|via=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \u226512 injuries\n| power outages = \n| maximum snow = \n| gusts = \n| hail = {{convert|1.75|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n| tornado duration = 24 hours\n| image = December 16\u201317, 2019 tornado outbreak warnings and reports.png\n| fujitascale = EF3\n| tornadoes = 40\n| lowest temperature = \n| lowest pressure = \n| active = December 16, 2019 - December 17, 2019\n| type = [[Tornado outbreak]]\n| caption = Map of tornado warnings and confirmed tornadoes from the outbreak\n| partof = the '''[[Tornadoes of 2019|tornado outbreaks of 2019]]'''\n}}\n\nThe '''tornado outbreak of December 16\u201317, 2019''' was a significant severe weather event that affected the [[Southern United States]]. Discrete [[supercell]]s developed in the early morning on December 16 and moved northeast, spawning multiple strong, long-tracked tornadoes in cities such as [[Alexandria, Louisiana|Alexandria]] and in [[Laurel, Mississippi|Laurel]] before congealing into an eastward-moving squall line. During the outbreak, the National Weather Service issued several [[Particularly_Dangerous_Situation#PDS_Tornado_Warning|PDS tornado warnings]] as well as a rare [[tornado emergency]] for Alexandria. In addition to this, the Storm Prediction Center issued six [[tornado watch]]es for the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/191216_rpts.html|title=191216's Storm Reports|publisher=[[NOAA]]|accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref> The event happened to take place on the same date of another outbreak in a similar area 19 years earlier.\n\n==Meteorological synopsis==\n[[File:December 16th, 2019 Lake Charles Radiosonde Launch.jpg|thumb|left|Lake Charles Sounding at 1800z on December 16, 2019]]\nThe first signs of organized severe weather came on December&nbsp;12, when the [[Storm Prediction Center]] (SPC) outlined a day 5 risk area across portions of the Mid-South and lower Ohio River Valley.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/exper/day4-8/archive/2019/day4-8_20191212.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Day 4-8 Severe Weather Outlook Page|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref> This 15% delineation area was shifted southwestward the following day and translated to a broad Slight risk for severe weather on December&nbsp;14.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/exper/day4-8/archive/2019/day4-8_20191213.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Day 4-8 Severe Weather Outlook Page|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2019/day3otlk_20191214_0830.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Dec 14, 2019 0830 UTC Day 3 Severe Thunderstorm Outlook|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref> In their first day 2 outlook, the SPC introduced an Enhanced risk across portions of Louisiana, Mississippi, and Alabama.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2019/day2otlk_20191215_0700.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Dec 15, 2019 0700 UTC Day 2 Convective Outlook|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref> By the late morning of December&nbsp;16, a Moderate risk area was introduced from eastern Louisiana through central Mississippi.<ref name=\"SPC1630\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2019/day1otlk_20191216_1630.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Dec 16, 2019 1630 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref>\n[[File:EF3 damage Mize MS.jpg|thumb|EF3 damage to a house near Mize, Mississippi.]]\nExpectations of a tornado outbreak arose on December&nbsp;16 as a well-defined, positively-tilted [[Trough (meteorology)|trough]] existed across the central United States and very strong cyclonic flow developed southeast of this feature. At the surface, a cold front was expected to progress across the Southeast United States while an intensifying area of low pressure propagated northeast along the boundary. The environment along and ahead of this front was anticipated to be favorable for severe weather, featuring dewpoints as high as the low 70s Fahrenheit, mid-level Convective Available Potential Energy on the order of 1,000\u20132,000&nbsp;J/kg, and a {{convert|40\u201360|kn|mph|abbr=on}} contributing to large hodographs and strong cyclonic updraft potential. In addition, advection of drier air aloft was predicted to inhibit convective development until later in the day. Given the general alignment of the cold front and wind shear aloft, the SPC was uncertain early on December&nbsp;16 over whether numerous discrete supercells would exist in the highest threat area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2019/day1otlk_20191216_1300.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Dec 16, 2019 1300 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref> By later in the day, however, a consistent signal for sustained warm-sector supercells from available model guidance lent credibility to the potential for multiple significant tornadoes.<ref name=\"SPC1630\" /> At 16:40&nbsp;UTC, the SPC issued their first tornado watch, the first of four during the day as the severe weather threat spread eastward.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2019/ww0700.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Tornado Watch 700|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref> Discrete supercells soon developed within the warm sector across Louisiana, while a line of thunderstorms congealed along the encroaching cold front.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md2209.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 2209|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref> Numerous tornadoes, some strong to intense, were observed across Louisiana and Mississippi throughout the afternoon hours. By late evening, isolated supercells were overtaken by the squall line, reducing the significant tornado threat. The following morning, the storms propagated eastward into Georgia, where a few additional tornadoes occurred before the outbreak came to an end.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md2219.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 2219|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref>\n\n==Confirmed tornadoes==\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 40\n|FU = 0\n|F0 = 13\n|F1 = 13\n|F2 = 9\n|F3 = 5\n|F4 = 0\n|F5 = 0\n|Enhanced=yes\n}}\n\n===December 16 event===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|+ List of confirmed tornadoes \u2013 Monday, December 16, 2019{{efn|All dates are based on the local [[time zone]] where the tornado touched down; however, all times are in [[Coordinated Universal Time]] for consistency.|group=note|name=Date/Time}}\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:3%; text-align:center;\"|[[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF#]]\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:7%; text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\"|Location\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\"|County / parish\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:5%; text-align:center;\"|State\n! scope=\"col\"  