ama|Bibb]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|33.0416|-86.9401|name=Brierfield (Dec. 16, EF1)}}\n|04:00\u201304:04\n|{{convert|2.6|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|300|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Dozens of trees were snapped or uprooted, and a barn was damaged as well.\n|<ref name=\"1216BMX\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|E of [[Montevallo, Alabama|Montevallo]]\n|[[Shelby County, Alabama|Shelby]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|33.0851|-86.8429|name=Montevallo (Dec. 16, EF0)}}\n|04:07\u201304:12\n|{{convert|2.29|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|200|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|An outbuilding was destroyed, two mobile homes suffered minor damage, and dozens of trees were snapped or uprooted. A house sustained minor roof damage, and a deputy sheriff was blown off the road in his vehicle.\n|<ref name=\"1216BMX\" />\n|-\n|}\n\n===December 17 event===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|+ List of confirmed tornadoes \u2013 Tuesday, December 17, 2019{{efn|All dates are based on the local [[time zone]] where the tornado touched down; however, all times are in [[Coordinated Universal Time]] for consistency.|group=note|name=Date/Time}}\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:3%; text-align:center;\"|[[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF#]]\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:7%; text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\"|Location\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\"|County / parish\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:5%; text-align:center;\"|State\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Start coord.\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Time ([[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]])\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Path length\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Max width\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:48%; text-align:center;\"|Summary\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:3%; text-align:center;\"|Refs\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|N of [[Rock Hill, Georgia|Rock Hill]]\n|[[Early County, Georgia|Early]]\n|[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]]\n|{{Coord|31.355|-85.0228|name=Rock Hill (Dec. 17, EF0)}}\n|12:30\u201312:33\n|{{convert|0.39|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|50|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|A few trees were snapped and blown in opposing directions.\n|<ref name=\"1217TAE\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=NWS Damage Survey for 12/17/19 Tornado Event - Update 2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=201912180058|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=December 17, 2019|accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|[[Madrid, Alabama|Madrid]]\n|[[Houston County, Alabama|Houston]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|31.03|-85.39|name=Madrid (Dec. 17, EF0)}}\n|12:52\n|<!--{{convert|6.57|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}-->unknown\n|<!--{{convert|200|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}-->unknown\n|One home lost a garage and outbuilding. A few dozen softwood trees were uprooted or snapped.\n|<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=Preliminary Local Storm Report|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=LSRTAE&e=201912201913|date=December 20, 2019|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat1}} | EF1\n|E of [[Jeterville, Georgia|Jeterville]]\n|[[Miller County, Georgia|Miller]]\n|[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]]\n|{{Coord|31.2046|-84.7031|name=Jeterville (Dec. 17, EF1)}}\n|14:27\u201314:36\n|{{convert|6.57|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|200|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Barns, trees, and farm equipment was damaged.\n|<ref name=\"1217TAE\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|WSW of [[Newton, Georgia|Newton]]\n|[[Baker County, Georgia|Baker]]\n|[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]]\n|{{Coord|31.3074|-84.3932|name=Newton (Dec. 17, EF0)}}\n|15:00\u201315:02\n|{{convert|0.2|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|75|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Several trees were snapped, a mobile home was slid off its support about {{convert|3|ft|m|abbr=on}} and had its roof damaged, and an irrigation pivot was damaged.\n|<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=Brief EF-0 Tornado Confirmed in Baker County Georgia|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=201912191627|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=December 19, 2019|accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat2}} | EF2\n|W of [[Ocilla, Georgia|Ocilla]] to E of [[Ashton, Georgia|Ashton]]\n|[[Irwin County, Georgia|Irwin]], [[Ben Hill County, Georgia|Ben Hill]]\n|[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]]\n|{{Coord|31.5926|-83.399|name=Ocilla (Dec. 17, EF2)}}\n|16:35\u201317:09\n|{{convert|19.2|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|400|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Hundreds of trees were snapped by this high-end EF2 tornado, and several homes were severely damaged and sustained roof loss. The most severe damage occurred at Donelson Christian Academy in [[Mystic, Georgia|Mystic]], where multiple brick buildings had roofs torn off and sustained collapse of exterior walls. Barns and outbuildings were heavily damaged or destroyed, irrigation machinery was damaged, and a couple RVs were rolled over and heavily damaged.\n|<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=EF-2 Tornado Confirmed in Irwin County Georgia|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=201912191602|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=December 19, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notable tornadoes==\n===DeRidder \u2013 Rosepine \u2013 Alexandria \u2013 Pineville, Lousiana===\n[[File:AlexandriaLouisianaEF3tornado2019.jpg|thumb|left|EF3 damage to the Hope Baptist School in Alexandria, Louisiana.]]\nDuring the afternoon of December 16, a strong, long-tracked and damaging tornado touched down in [[DeRidder, Louisiana]]. The tornado was initially weak, causing minor EF0 to EF1 tree and roof damage in DeRidder. The tornado exited DeRidder, widening and strengthening as it continued northeastward into [[Vernon Parish, Louisiana|Vernon Parish]] and reaching EF3 strength as it passed to the southeast of [[Rosepine, Louisiana|Rosepine]]. Severe damage occurred along Mac Sterling Road, John Brewer Road, and Borel Road, where a couple of manufactured homes were obliterated with the debris scattered long distances through nearby fields. Outbuildings were destroyed, many large trees were snapped or uprooted, and some frame homes sustained partial to total roof loss. A few of these frame homes sustained some collapse of exterior walls as well. A 59-year old woman was killed in her home by the tornado in this area. The tornado weakened back to EF1 strength as it continued to the northeast, crossing [[Louisiana Highway 10]], where a church lost a portion of its metal roof and outbuildings were destroyed. Numerous trees were snapped as well. EF2 damage occurred beyond this point as the tornado moved through forested areas of [[Fort Polk]], snapping and uprooting countless trees. A structure sustained loss of its metal roof and collapse of brick facade in this area as well.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref> Exiting Fort Polk, the tornado narrowed and weakened again, causing EF0 to EF1 tree damage is it moved through unpopulated areas. Additional minor EF0 and EF1 tree damage occurred as the tornado continued into [[Rapides Parish, Louisiana|Rapides Parish]], moving to the northeast as it passed near [[Hineston, Louisiana|Hineston]] and [[Otis, Louisiana|Otis]]. Restrengthening then occurred as extensive EF2 tree damage occurred near the Kincaid Reservoir. Numerous trees were snapped and denuded, and a few sustained some low-end debarking. Maintaining EF2 strength, the strong tornado then entered the west side of [[Alexandria, Louisiana|Alexandria]]. Numerous mobile homes were thrown and destroyed at a mobile home sales business along Ross Lane, while nearby homes sustained significant roof damage. A few outbuildings were destroyed as well. The tornado strengthened and widened further just past this location, producing EF3 damage along Stovall Road. Several large metal buildings were completely destroyed in this area, and a large portion of the nearby Hope Baptist School was destroyed at EF3 intensity as well, with large amounts of debris was scattered throughout the area. The tornado then crossed [[Louisiana Highway 28]] and heavily damaged a sports complex along the north side of the highway. Continuing to the east-northeast, additional EF3 damage occurred as a convenience store was destroyed, and a nearby large metal-framed warehouse building was destroyed as well along John Allison Drive.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref> A manufactured home was overturned in this area as well. In a nearby residential area, the tornado weakened to EF2 strength as large trees were downed, and homes had large portions of their roofs torn off. Continuing to the northeast through Alexandria, the tornado narrowed and weakened to EF1 strength, damaging trees and power poles as it crossed Bayou Rapides Road. Along Enterprise Road, a warehouse building sustained EF1 damage to its roof and doors. The tornado proceeded to cross the [[Red River of the South|Red River]] and entered [[Pineville, Louisiana|Pineville]], first causing EF1 damage to structures at the Pineville Municipal Airport. The tornado moved along a northeasterly path through residential areas of Pineville, snapping and uprooting numerous large trees. Some of these trees fell onto houses and caused heavy damage. A majority of the damage in Pineville was rated EF1, though a small pocket of EF2 damage occurred along Edgewood Drive, where a house sustained considerable structural damage. Past this area, the tornado continued to narrow and weaken, eventually dissipating after producing some EF0 tree limb damage along Donahue Ferry Road in Pineville.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\nOverall, this EF3 tornado caused one fatality along its 62-mile long path. It had a peak width of {{convert|400|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Lake Charles, Louisiana|title=NWS Damage Survey for 12/16/19 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLCH&e=201912182057|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=December 18, 2019|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\n===Laurel \u2013 Sandersville \u2013 Shubuta \u2013 Mannassa, Mississippi/Lisman, Alabama===\n[[File:LaurelMississippiEF3tornado2019.jpg|thumb|left|EF3 damage to the Wade Services manufacturing plant near Laurel, Mississippi.]]\nThis strong, long-tracked tornado touched down during the late evening hours of December 16, at Hesler Noble Field in southwestern [[Laurel, Mississippi]]. Past the airport, the tornado caused EF0 to EF1 damage at the Dixie Golf Club, where trees and tree limbs were snapped and fencing was blown over. The tornado moved along a northeastward path through the southwest side of Laurel, downing trees and causing minor roof damage to homes. Metal roofing was torn off of a three-story motel along Jefferson street as well. Damage along this section of the path was rated EF0 to EF1 in intensity. Crossing South 16th Avenue, the tornado reached EF2 strength, where a small brick office building sustained roof and exterior wall loss, and a strip mall was heavily damaged. The roof of a hotel was lifted up and dropped back down onto the building, and a semi-truck and flatbed trailer carrying automobiles was flipped over and dragged. Continuing to the northeast through Laurel, the tornado weakened back to EF1 strength as numerous homes, warehouses, apartment buildings, and other structures sustained minor to moderate roof damage. One large building lost roughly 20% of its metal roof, and sustained collapse of brick facade. A [[Piggly Wiggly]] grocery store also sustained minor EF0 roof and exterior damage in this area as well, and numerous trees and a few power poles were downed. The tornado continued to the northeast through residential neighborhoods at EF1 intensity, snapping and uprooting trees and causing roof damage to additional homes. Some trees fell onto houses and cars as well. A metal self-storage building was partially destroyed along North 1st Avenue, and a large warehouse building near North Railroad Avenue sustained considerable roof damage. The tornado reached EF2 intensity again as moved through the eastern part of Laurel, where a house had its roof torn off and other homes sustained lesser roof damage. The Nora Davis Magnet school also lost much of its roof in this area. The tornado then reached EF3 intensity as it exited Laurel and crossed [[Interstate 59]], snapping and uprooting numerous trees, and toppling several large metal truss transmission towers to the ground. EF3 damage continued as the tornado then completely destroyed the Wade Services manufacturing plant, along with several other metal buildings and an office building on the property. Northeast of this area, the tornado momentarily weakened and caused EF1 tree damage as it moved along the east side of Interstate 59. The tornado became strong again as it then impacted the southern fringes of [[Sandersville, Mississippi|Sandersville]] at EF2 strength, where a house sustained loss of much of its roof, along with some second floor exterior walls. Another home sustained major roof damage, outbuildings were damaged or destroyed, numerous large trees were snapped or uprooted, and two people sustained minor injuries in the Sandersville area.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref> Past Sandersville, the tornado weakened back to EF1 strength as it struck the Mississippi Choctaw Reservation, where homes sustained roof and garage damage, a small pavilion collapsed, trees were downed, and headstones were tipped over at a cemetery. EF0 and EF1 damage to trees and homes continued through the extreme northwestern corner of [[Wayne County, Mississippi|Wayne County]] and into the southwestern corner of [[Clarke County, Mississippi|Clarke County]], though a small pocket of EF2 damage occurred along County Road 223, where numerous large trees were snapped and a mobile home was rolled and destroyed. Additional EF2 damage occurred as the tornado crossed [[U.S. Route 45]] north of [[Shubuta, Mississippi|Shubuta]], where a well-built home had most if its roof torn off. Northeast of Shubuta, numerous trees were snapped and uprooted at EF1 strength as the tornado moved through rural areas. A few outbuildings and mobile homes were damaged as well. A final area of EF2 damage occurred to the southwest of the small community of [[Mannassa, Mississippi|Mannassa]], where a well-built home along County Road 664 sustained destruction of its attached garage, and had a large portion of its roof torn off. A nearby mobile home was rolled and destroyed as well. Northeast of Mannassa, the tornado weakened to EF0 strength as it approached the Alabama border, causing only tree limb damage in rural areas. The tornado then regained EF1 strength as it crossed into [[Choctaw County, Alabama]], downing trees and destroying a mobile home. Additional trees were snapped or uprooted, and a house sustained partial removal of its roof before the tornado dissipated to the west-northwest of [[Lisman, Alabama]] after traveling {{convert|61.31|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\nThe tornado was rated EF3 and injured two people. It reached a peak width of {{convert|350|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=865251</ref><ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2019 tornado outbreaks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tornado outbreak of December 16-17, 2019}}\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Alabama]]\n[[Category:2019 in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:2019 in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:2019 in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:December 2019 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2019 natural disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes of 2019]]\n[[Category:F3 tornadoes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox storm\n| name = Tornado outbreak of December 16\u201317, 2019\n| highest winds = {{convert|158|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}\n| enhanced = yes\n| current advisories = \n| affected = [[Louisiana]], [[Mississippi]], [[Alabama]], [[Tennessee]], [[Florida]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| total fatalities = 3 (+1 non-tornadic) fatalities<ref name=WSB>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsbtv.com/news/trending/deep-south-tornadoes-3-killed-alabama-louisiana-storms-slam-region-officials-say/CERA4K3FHRBPHETEWDRPH2FBK4/|title=Southeast tornadoes: 4 killed in Alabama, Louisiana and Kentucky after storms slam region|last=|first=|date=December 17, 2019|website=WSB-TV|via=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \u226512 injuries\n| power outages = \n| maximum snow = \n| gusts = \n| hail = {{convert|1.75|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n| tornado duration = 24 hours\n| image = December 16\u201317, 2019 tornado outbreak warnings and reports.png\n| fujitascale = EF3\n| tornadoes = 40\n| lowest temperature = \n| lowest pressure = \n| active = December 16, 2019 - December 17, 2019\n| type = [[Tornado outbreak]]\n| caption = Map of tornado warnings and confirmed tornadoes from the outbreak\n| partof = the '''[[Tornadoes of 2019|tornado outbreaks of 2019]]'''\n}}\n\nThe '''tornado outbreak of December 16\u201317, 2019''' was a significant severe weather event that affected the [[Southern United States]]. Discrete [[supercell]]s developed in the early morning on December 16 and moved northeast, spawning multiple strong tornadoes in cities such as [[Alexandria, Louisiana|Alexandria]] and in [[Laurel, Mississippi|Laurel]] before congealing into an eastward-moving squall line. During the outbreak, the National Weather Service issued several [[Particularly_Dangerous_Situation#PDS_Tornado_Warning|PDS tornado warnings]] as well as a rare [[tornado emergency]] for Alexandria. In addition to this, the Storm Prediction Center issued six [[tornado watch]]es for the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/191216_rpts.html|title=191216's Storm Reports|publisher=[[NOAA]]|accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref> The event happened to take place on the same date of another outbreak in a similar area 19 years earlier.\n\n==Meteorological synopsis==\n[[File:December 16th, 2019 Lake Charles Radiosonde Launch.jpg|thumb|left|Lake Charles Sounding at 1800z on December 16, 2019]]\nThe first signs of organized severe weather came on December&nbsp;12, when the [[Storm Prediction Center]] (SPC) outlined a day 5 risk area across portions of the Mid-South and lower Ohio River Valley.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/exper/day4-8/archive/2019/day4-8_20191212.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Day 4-8 Severe Weather Outlook Page|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref> This 15% delineation area was shifted southwestward the following day and translated to a broad Slight risk for severe weather on December&nbsp;14.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/exper/day4-8/archive/2019/day4-8_20191213.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Day 4-8 Severe Weather Outlook Page|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2019/day3otlk_20191214_0830.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Dec 14, 2019 0830 UTC Day 3 Severe Thunderstorm Outlook|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref> In their first day 2 outlook, the SPC introduced an Enhanced risk across portions of Louisiana, Mississippi, and Alabama.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2019/day2otlk_20191215_0700.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Dec 15, 2019 0700 UTC Day 2 Convective Outlook|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref> By the late morning of December&nbsp;16, a Moderate risk area was introduced from eastern Louisiana through central Mississippi.<ref name=\"SPC1630\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2019/day1otlk_20191216_1630.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Dec 16, 2019 1630 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref>\n[[File:EF3 damage Mize MS.jpg|thumb|EF3 damage to a house near Mize, Mississippi.]]\nExpectations of a tornado outbreak arose on December&nbsp;16 as a well-defined, positively-tilted [[Trough (meteorology)|trough]] existed across the central United States and very strong cyclonic flow developed southeast of this feature. At the surface, a cold front was expected to progress across the Southeast United States while an intensifying area of low pressure propagated northeast along the boundary. The environment along and ahead of this front was anticipated to be favorable for severe weather, featuring dewpoints as high as the low 70s Fahrenheit, mid-level Convective Available Potential Energy on the order of 1,000\u20132,000&nbsp;J/kg, and a {{convert|40\u201360|kn|mph|abbr=on}} contributing to large hodographs and strong cyclonic updraft potential. In addition, advection of drier air aloft was predicted to inhibit convective development until later in the day. Given the general alignment of the cold front and wind shear aloft, the SPC was uncertain early on December&nbsp;16 over whether numerous discrete supercells would exist in the highest threat area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2019/day1otlk_20191216_1300.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Dec 16, 2019 1300 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref> By later in the day, however, a consistent signal for sustained warm-sector supercells from available model guidance lent credibility to the potential for multiple significant tornadoes.<ref name=\"SPC1630\" /> At 16:40&nbsp;UTC, the SPC issued their first tornado watch, the first of four during the day as the severe weather threat spread eastward.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2019/ww0700.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Tornado Watch 700|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref> Discrete supercells soon developed within the warm sector across Louisiana, while a line of thunderstorms congealed along the encroaching cold front.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md2209.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 2209|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref> Numerous tornadoes, some strong to intense, were observed across Louisiana and Mississippi throughout the afternoon hours. By late evening, isolated supercells were overtaken by the squall line, reducing the significant tornado threat. The following morning, the storms propagated eastward into Georgia, where a few additional tornadoes occurred before the outbreak came to an end.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md2219.html|title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 2219|website=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref>\n\n==Confirmed tornadoes==\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 40\n|FU = 0\n|F0 = 13\n|F1 = 13\n|F2 = 9\n|F3 = 5\n|F4 = 0\n|F5 = 0\n|Enhanced=yes\n}}\n\n===December 16 event===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|+ List of confirmed tornadoes \u2013 Monday, December 16, 2019{{efn|All dates are based on the local [[time zone]] where the tornado touched down; however, all times are in [[Coordinated Universal Time]] for consistency.|group=note|name=Date/Time}}\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:3%; text-align:center;\"|[[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF#]]\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:7%; text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\"|Location\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\"|County / parish\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:5%; text-align:center;\"|State\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Start coord.\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Time ([[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]])\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Path length\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Max width\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:48%; text-align:center;\"|Summary\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:3%; text-align:center;\"|Refs\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat1}} | EF1\n|N of [[Red Chute, Louisiana|Red Chute]] to W of [[Homer, Louisiana|Homer]]\n|[[Webster Parish, Louisiana|Webster]], [[Claiborne Parish, Louisiana|Claiborne]], [[Bossier Parish, Louisiana|Bossier]]\n|[[Louisiana|LA]]\n|{{Coord|32.6336|-93.602|name=Red Chute (Dec. 16, EF1)}}\n|16:10\u201316:50\n|{{convert|26.28|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|250|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Several hundred trees were snapped or uprooted. One home lost most of its roof, toppling a brick wall. A second home also had most of its roof ripped off. A single-wide mobile home was lifted and carried about {{convert|50|yd|m|abbr=on}}, with the undercarriage of the structure wrapped around a tree and the remains destroyed.\n|<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Shreveport, Louisiana|title=Significant Update on North Louisiana 12/16/19 Tornado|url=https://mesonet.a