ttern_so3 = _mufc0305a\n | leftarm3 = FFFFFF | body3 = FFFFFF | rightarm3 = FFFFFF | shorts3 = FFFFFF | socks3 = FFFFFF\n| prevseason         = [[2002\u201303 Manchester United F.C. season|2002\u201303]]\n| nextseason         = [[2004\u201305 Manchester United F.C. season|2004\u201305]]\n}}\nThe 2003\u201304 season was [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]'s 12th season in the [[Premier League]], and their 29th consecutive season in the top division of [[Football in England|English football]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stretfordend.co.uk/seasons/season2004.html |title=Manchester United Season 2003/04 |accessdate=8 October 2007 |publisher=StretfordEnd.co.uk }}</ref>\n\nUnited started the season by winning the [[2003 FA Community Shield]] and then secured a record eleventh [[FA Cup]] with a 3\u20130 win over [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] at the [[Millennium Stadium]] in [[Cardiff]]. However, the club surrendered the Premier League title to unbeaten champions [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], with a second-half dip in league form coinciding with [[Rio Ferdinand]] starting an eight-month ban from football due to a missed drugs test and restricting United to a third-place finish.\n\nNew to the United side were Portuguese winger [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], Brazilian [[2002 FIFA World Cup]]-winning midfielder [[Jos\u00e9 Kl\u00e9berson|Kl\u00e9berson]], American goalkeeper [[Tim Howard]], Cameroonian midfielder [[Eric Djemba-Djemba]] and French striker [[David Bellion]].\n\nUnited's [[UEFA Champions League]] and [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] dreams ended in the last 16, with the European exit being particularly painful as a last minute goal by eventual champions [[FC Porto|Porto]] put them out of the competition and denied them an eighth successive Champions League quarter-final.\n\n==Pre-season and friendlies==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Opponents\n!H/A\n!Result<br />F\u2013A\n!Scorers\n!Attendance\n|- bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|22 July 2003\n|[[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]\n|[[CenturyLink Field|N]]\n|[https://web.archive.org/web/20050411212047/http://www.manutd.com/news/fullstory.sps?iNewsID=39791&itype=466&iCategoryID=120 4\u20130]\n|[[Ruud van Nistelrooy|Van Nistelrooy]] 7', [[Ryan Giggs|Giggs]] 27', [[Ole Gunnar Solskj\u00e6r|Solskj\u00e6r]] 39', [[David Bellion|Bellion]] 72'\n|66,722\n|- bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|27 July 2003\n|[[Club Am\u00e9rica]]\n|[[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum|N]]\n|[https://web.archive.org/web/20041226034355/http://www.manutd.com/news/fullstory.sps?iNewsId=39976&itype=466&icategoryid=120 3\u20131]\n|[[Ruud van Nistelrooy|Van Nistelrooy]] 48', [[Diego Forl\u00e1n|Forl\u00e1n]] (2) 49', 80'\n|57,365\n|- bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|31 July 2003\n|[[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]\n|[[Giants Stadium|N]]\n|[https://web.archive.org/web/20040805045449/http://www.manutd.com/news/fullstory.sps?iNewsID=40318&itype=466&iCategoryID=120 4\u20131]\n|[[Ryan Giggs|Giggs]] 25', [[Paul Scholes|Scholes]] 57', [[Ruud van Nistelrooy|Van Nistelrooy]] 60', [[Ole Gunnar Solskj\u00e6r|Solskj\u00e6r]] 79'\n|79,000\n|- bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|3 August 2003\n|[[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n|[[Lincoln Financial Field|N]]\n|[https://web.archive.org/web/20040909231647/http://www.manutd.com/news/fullstory.sps?iNewsID=40479&itype=466&iCategoryID=120 3\u20131]\n|[[Diego Forl\u00e1n|Forl\u00e1n]] (2) 25', 37', [[Ruud van Nistelrooy|Van Nistelrooy]] 85'\n|68,396\n|- bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"\n|7 August 2003\n|[[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]]\n|A\n|[https://web.archive.org/web/20031008002752/http://www.manutd.com/news/fullstory.sps?iNewsID=40731&itype=466&iCategoryID=120 1\u20133]\n|[[Hugo (footballer, born 1976)|Hugo]] 88' ([[Own goal|o.g.]])\n|55,000\n|- bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"\n|13 August 2003\n|[[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]\n|A\n|1\u20133\n|[[Diego Forl\u00e1n|Forl\u00e1n]] 68'\n|\n|}\n\n==FA Community Shield==\n{{main article|2003 FA Community Shield}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Opponents\n!H/A\n!Result