{"title_page": "Wolfram code", "text_new": "'''Wolfram code''' is a naming system often used for one-dimensional [[cellular automaton]] rules, introduced by [[Stephen Wolfram]] in a 1983 paper<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wolfram|first=Stephen|title=Statistical Mechanics of Cellular Automata|journal=Reviews of Modern Physics|volume=55|pages=601\u2013644|date=July 1983|doi=10.1103/RevModPhys.55.601|bibcode=1983RvMP...55..601W}}</ref> and used in his book ''[[A New Kind of Science]]''.<ref>Wolfram, Stephen, ''[http://www.wolframscience.com/nksonline A New Kind of Science]''. Wolfram Media, Inc., May 14, 2002. {{ISBN|1-57955-008-8}}</ref>\n\nThe code is based on the observation that a table specifying the new state of each cell in the automaton, as a function of the states in its neighborhood, may be interpreted as a ''k''-digit number in the ''S''-ary positional number system, where ''S'' is the number of states that each cell in the automaton may have, ''k''&nbsp;=&nbsp;S<sup>2''n''&nbsp;+&nbsp;1</sup> is the number of neighborhood configurations, and ''n'' is the radius of the neighborhood. Thus, the Wolfram code for a particular rule is a number in the range from 0 to ''S''<sup>''S''<sup>{{nowrap|2''n'' + 1}}</sup></sup>&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;1, converted from ''S''-ary to [[decimal]] notation. It may be calculated as follows:\n\n# List all the ''S''<sup>2''n''&nbsp;+&nbsp;1</sup> possible state configurations of the neighbourhood of a given cell.\n# Interpreting each configuration as a number as described above, sort them in descending numerical order.\n# For each configuration, list the state which the given cell will have, according to this rule, on the next iteration.\n# Interpret the resulting list of states again as an ''S''-ary number, and convert this number to decimal.  The resulting decimal number is the Wolfram code.\n\nThe Wolfram code does not specify the size (nor shape) of the neighbourhood, nor the number of states \u2014 these are assumed to be known from context.  When used on their own without such context, the codes are often assumed to refer to the class of [[Elementary cellular automaton|elementary cellular automata]], two-state one-dimensional cellular automata with a (contiguous) three-cell neighbourhood, which Wolfram extensively investigates in his book.  Notable rules in this class include [[rule 30]], [[rule 110]], and [[rule 184]]. [[Rule 90]] is also interesting because it creates [[Pascal's Triangle]] modulo 2. A code of this type suffixed by an R, such as \"Rule 37R\", indicates a [[second-order cellular automaton]] with the same neighborhood structure.\n\nWhile in a strict sense every Wolfram code in the valid range defines a different rule, some of these rules are [[isomorphic]] and usually considered equivalent.  For example, rule 110 above is isomorphic with the rules 124, 137 and 193, <!-- I think I got these right, please fix if not --> which can be obtained from the original by left-right reflection and by renumbering the states.  By convention, each such isomorphism class is represented by the rule with the lowest code number in it.  A disadvantage of the Wolfram notation, and the use of decimal notation in particular, is that it makes such isomorphisms harder to see than some alternative notations.  Despite this, it has become the [[de facto standard]] way of referring to one-dimensional cellular automata.\n\n== Generalized cellular automata ==\nThe number of possible rules, ''R'', for a generalized cellular automaton in which each cell may assume one of ''S'' states as determined by a neighborhood size of ''n'', in a ''D''-dimensional space is given by:\n''R=S<sup>S<span><sup>(2n+1)<span><sup>D</sup></span></sup></span></sup>\n\nThe most common example has ''S = 2'', ''n = 1'' and ''D = 1'', giving ''R = 256''.  It should be noted that the number of possible rules has an extreme dependence on the dimensionality of the system.  For example, increasing the number of dimensions (''D'') from 1 to 2 increases the number of possible rules from 256 to ''2<sup>512</sup>'' (which is ''~1.341&times;10<sup>154</sup>'').\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Wolfram code| 01]]\n[[Category:Cellular automata]]\n", "text_old": "'''Wolfram code''' is a naming system often used for one-dimensional [[cellular automaton]] rules, introduced by [[Stephen Wolfram]] in a 1983 paper<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wolfram|first=Stephen|title=Statistical Mechanics of Cellular Automata|journal=Reviews of Modern Physics|volume=55|pages=601\u2013644|date=July 1983|doi=10.1103/RevModPhys.55.601|bibcode=1983RvMP...55..601W}}</ref> and used in his book ''[[A New Kind of Science]]''.<ref>Wolfram, Stephen, ''[http://www.wolframscience.com/nksonline A New Kind of Science]''. Wolfram Media, Inc., May 14, 2002. {{ISBN|1-57955-008-8}}</ref>\n\nThe code is based on the observation that a table specifying the new state of each cell in the automaton, as a function of the states in its neighborhood, may be interpreted as a ''k''-digit number in the ''S''-ary positional number system, where ''S'' is the number of states that each cell in the automaton may have, ''k''&nbsp;=&nbsp;S<sup>2''n''&nbsp;+&nbsp;1</sup> is the number of neighborhood configurations, and ''n'' is the radius of the neighborhood. Thus, the Wolfram code for a particular rule is a number in the range from 0 to ''S''<sup>''S''<sup>{{nowrap|2''n'' + 1}}</sup></sup>&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;1, converted from ''S''-ary to [[decimal]] notation. It may be calculated as follows:\n\n# List all the ''S''<sup>2''n''&nbsp;+&nbsp;1</sup> possible state configurations of the neighbourhood of a given cell.\n# Interpreting each configuration as a number as described above, sort them in descending numerical order.\n# For each configuration, list the state which the given cell will have, according to this rule, on the next iteration.\n# Interpret the resulting list of states again as an ''S''-ary number, and convert this number to decimal.  The resulting decimal number is the Wolfram code.\n\nThe Wolfram code does not specify the size (nor shape) of the neighbourhood, nor the number of states \u2014 these are assumed to be known from context.  When used on their own without such context, the codes are often assumed to refer to the class of [[Elementary cellular automaton|elementary cellular automata]], two-state one-dimensional cellular automata with a (contiguous) three-cell neighbourhood, which Wolfram extensively investigates in his book.  Notable rules in this class include [[rule 30]], [[rule 110]], and [[rule 184]]. [[Rule 90]] is also interesting because it creates [[Pascal's Triangle]] modulo 2. A code of this type suffixed by an R, such as \"Rule 37R\", indicates a [[second-order cellular automaton]] with the same neighborhood structure.\n\nWhile in a strict sense every Wolfram code in the valid range defines a different rule, some of these rules are [[isomorphic]] and usually considered equivalent.  For example, rule 110 above is isomorphic with the rules 124, 137 and 193, <!-- I think I got these right, please fix if not --> which can be obtained from the original by left-right reflection and by renumbering the states.  By convention, each such isomorphism class is represented by the rule with the lowest code number in it.  A disadvantage of the Wolfram notation, and the use of decimal notation in particular, is that it makes such isomorphisms harder to see than some alternative notations.  Despite this, it has become the [[de facto standard]] way of referring to one-dimensional cellular automata.\n\n== Generalized cellular automata ==\nThe number of possible rules, ''R'', for a generalized cellular automaton in which each cell may assume one of ''S'' states as determined by a neighborhood size of ''n'', in a ''D''-dimensional space is given by:\n''R=S<sup>S<span><sup>(2n+1)<span><sup>D</sup></span></sup></span></sup>\n\nThe most common example has ''S = 2'', ''n = 1'' and ''D = 1'', giving ''R = 256''.  It should be noticed that the number of possible rules has an extreme dependence on the dimensionality of the system.  For example, increasing the number of dimensions (''D'') from 1 to 2 increases the number of possible rules from 256 to ''2<sup>512</sup>'' (which is ''~1.341&times;10<sup>154</sup>'').\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Wolfram code| 01]]\n[[Category:Cellular automata]]\n", "name_user": "OfficialURL", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGeneralized cellular automata", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolfram_code"}
{"title_page": "Trap Queen", "text_new": "{{use mdy dates |date=December 2019 }}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Trap Queen\n| cover      = Fetty Wap - Trap Queen.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Fetty Wap]]\n| album      = Up Next {{noitalic|and}} [[Fetty Wap (album)|Fetty Wap]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2014|4|22}}\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = March 2014\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n|genre=<!--Do not add unsourced genres -->| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=35}}\n| label      = {{hlist|RGF|[[300 Entertainment|300]]}}\n| writer     = [[Fetty Wap|Willie Maxwell]]\n| producer   = Tony Fadd\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Around the World (Natalie La Rose song)|Around the World]]\n| next_year  = 2015\n|misc={{External music video|{{YouTube|i_kF4zLNKio|\"Trap Queen\"}}}}}}\n\n\"'''Trap Queen'''\" is the debut single by American rapper [[Fetty Wap]] from his [[Fetty Wap (album)|self-titled debut album]] (2015). Following its online premiere in March 2014, it was released independently on April 22, 2014 before being re-released in conjunction with [[300 Entertainment]] on December 15, 2014. The song was well received by critics who praised the vocals and production for being cheery and infectious.\n\n\"Trap Queen\" was a [[sleeper hit]], becoming Fetty Wap's first entry on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in mid-2015 and ultimately went on to be a top ten hit, peaking at number two; the song spent 25 consecutive weeks in the top ten. Outside the United States, \"Trap Queen\" peaked within the top ten of the charts in Denmark and the United Kingdom. An accompanying [[music video]] for the song, directed by Nitt Da Gritt, was released on his [[YouTube]] page that features Wap and his girlfriend partying at their apartment. The song was written about his close friend, Mira Ginor, the real \"Trap Queen\". He first performed the song on television at the [[2015 MTV Movie Awards]] with [[Fall Out Boy]] and would make later appearances at ''[[The Tonight Show with Jimmy Fallon]]'', ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'', ''[[Nick Cannon Presents Wild 'n Out]]'' and the [[BET Awards 2015]] to perform the song. The song received two nominations at the [[58th Annual Grammy Awards|58th Grammy Awards]]: [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Song|Best Rap Song]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Performance|Best Rap Performance]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/6785974/grammy-nominations-2016-full-list | title=Grammy Nominations 2016: See the Full List of Nominees | publisher=Prometheus Global Media | work=Billboard | date=December 7, 2015 | accessdate=December 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Background and release==\nFetty Wap, a native of [[Paterson, New Jersey]], had been rapping and recording music locally as a member of the Remy Boyz 1738 rap troupe, which includes Montana \"Monty\" Buckz.<ref name=8things>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6472868/fetty-wap-8-things-to-know-trap-queen-kanye-west |title=Who Is Fetty Wap? 8 Things To Know about Kanye West's Latest Co-Sign |last=Lipshutz |first=Jason |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=February 13, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref> Wap conceived \"Trap Queen\" in late 2013 and recorded the song the following March after hearing what would become its [[backing track]], which had been produced by Tony Fadd of the Paterson-based RGF Productions.<ref name=bb_interview>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6494357/fetty-wap-trap-queen-interview |title='Trap Queen' Rapper Fetty Wap: 'I'ma Be the Youngest Rapper With One Eye, But a Lot of Money' |last=Kennedy |first=John |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=March 5, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref name=xxl_interview>{{cite web |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/the-break/2014/11/break-fetty-wap/ |title=The Break Presents: Fetty Wap |work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]] |publisher=[[Townsquare Media]] |date=November 18, 2014 |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref name=boombox>{{cite web |url=http://theboombox.com/fetty-wap-performs-trap-queen-intervew-nextup/ |title=Fetty Wap Performs 'Trap Queen,' Talks New Mixtape, Perseverance & More for 'Next Up' |last=Cline |first=Georgette |website=The Boombox |date=February 12, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref> It was the first recording on which Wap had sung, as he had been anxious to try \"something different\".<ref name=bb_interview/> The original studio recording consisted of three sung verses that Wap had [[freestyle rap|freestyled]] in the [[melody]] he had written.<ref name=bb_interview/><ref name=xxl_interview/> The recording was uploaded to [[SoundCloud]] shortly after in March 2014, where it soon began amassing plays.<ref name=8things/><ref name=soundcloud>{{cite web |url=https://soundcloud.com/harlem_fetty/fetty-wap-trap-queen-rough |title=Fetty Wap - Trap Queen by FettyWap1738 on SoundCloud |website=[[SoundCloud]] |date=March 8, 2014 |accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref> An extended version of the initial recording, featuring an additional spoken [[outro (music)|outro]], was included on Wap's ''Up Next'' [[mixtape]], which was initially sold locally in Paterson and later released online.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.audiomack.com/album/dj-louie-styles/up-next |title=Fetty Wap - Up Next |website=Audiomack |date=July 31, 2014 |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref name=hhdx/> This version of the song was also independently released on April 22, 2014 as a standalone [[music download|digital single]] under Goodfella4life Entertainment.<ref name=orig_release>{{cite web |url=https://us.7digital.com/artist/fetty-wap/release/trap-queen |title= Trap Queen (2014) |website=[[7digital]] |date=April 22, 2014 |accessdate=April 7, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150410044335/https://us.7digital.com/artist/fetty-wap/release/trap-queen |archivedate=April 10, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Wap had a feeling that \"Trap Queen\" was a potential [[hit single|hit]] even before recording the song, particularly when he first heard the beat,<ref name=bb_interview/><ref name=sxsw>{{cite web |url=http://schedule.sxsw.com/2015/events/event_MS32886 |title=Fetty Wap - 2015 SXSW Event Schedule |website=[[SXSW]] |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref> his suspicions that it could reach an audience outside his own region were confirmed later as he noticed its growing popularity on [[social media]] websites like [[Twitter]] and [[Instagram]];<ref name=observer>{{cite web |url=http://observer.com/2015/03/breakout-rap-sensation-fetty-wap-talks-texting-kanye-story-behind-trap-queen/ |title=Breakout Rap Sensation Fetty Wap Talks Texting Kanye, Story Behind 'Trap Queen' |last=LeDonne |first=Rob |work=[[The New York Observer]] |date=March 27, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref> meanwhile, its play count on SoundCloud had increased to over a million within its first months online.<ref name=hhdx>{{cite web |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.32303/title.fetty-wap-talks-trap-queen-origin-success |title=Fetty Wap Talks \"Trap Queen\" Origin & Success |last=Harris |first=Christopher |website=[[HipHopDX]] |publisher=Cheri Media Group |date=January 28, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150129173353/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.32303/title.fetty-wap-talks-trap-queen-origin-success |archivedate=29 January 2015}}</ref> To take advantage of the increased attention the song was receiving, a revised version was subsequently made for [[radio broadcasting|radio]]  which shortened the total runtime and included an additional rapped verse following the first iteration of the [[refrain|chorus]].<ref name=xxl_interview/>\n\nIn November 2014, Wap and RGF Productions partnered with [[Lyor Cohen]]'s label [[300 Entertainment]] to give \"Trap Queen\" a full-fledged commercial release.<ref name=insidethesuccess/> The two labels jointly issued the most recent edit of the single to [[online music store|digital retailers]] on December 15, 2014.<ref name=re-release>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/trap-queen-single/id949868742 |title=Trap Queen - Single by Fetty Wap |website=[[iTunes]] |date=December 15, 2014 |accessdate=April 7, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150405071055/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/trap-queen-single/id949868742 |archivedate=April 5, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n[[Songwriter|Written]] by Fetty Wap and [[Record producer|produced]] by Tony Fadd of RGF Productions, \"Trap Queen\" is a melodic [[lo-fi]] [[hip hop music|hip hop]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2018/04/can-the-weeknd-recapture-the-mystery|title=Can the Weeknd Recapture the Mystery?|last=Vanderhoof|first=Erin|date=April 19, 2018|website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref> [[trap music|trap]],<ref name=hhdx/><ref name=fuse>{{cite web |url=http://www.fuse.tv/videos/2015/03/fuse-favorite-fetty-wap |title=Fuse Favorite: Watch Fetty Wap on Fuse All Week |website=[[Fuse (TV channel)|Fuse]] |date=March 3, 2015 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref> and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6538507/trap-queen-fetty-wap-remix-slaptop | title=Slaptop Remixes Fetty Wap's 'Trap Queen' | magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | date=April 16, 2015 | accessdate=September 30, 2015 | author=Weiner, Natalie}}</ref> Wap sings most of the song's verses, along with its chorus, in a gritty, melodic delivery reminiscent of contemporary [[Southern hip hop]] artists such as [[Gucci Mane]], [[Future (rapper)|Future]], [[Rich Homie Quan]], and [[Young Thug]].<ref name=xxl_interview/><ref name=fuse/> Wap's sung vocals, particularly during the song's chorus, are [[audio signal processing|digitally altered]].<ref name=hhdx_adventure/><ref name=guardian/> One additional verse, following the first iteration of the chorus, is rapped in a more straightforward, traditional style. The song's beat is largely characterized by its trap percussion and [[synthesizer|synthesized]] chords.<ref name=guardian/>\n\nLyrically, \"Trap Queen\" is a giddy, affectionate tribute to a girlfriend and \"partner in crime\" whom Wap calls his trap queen.<ref name=insidethesuccess/><ref name=alibi>{{cite web |url=http://alibi.com/music/48728/Sonic-Reducer-Micro-reviews-of-Drake-and-Chief-Ke.html |title=Sonic Reducer |last=Pearson |first=Elliot |work=[[Weekly Alibi]] |date=March 26, 2015 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref> Wap has clarified that the song was written about an ex he had been dating and [[drug dealing|dealing]] [[crack cocaine]] with during his own time in [[crack house|the trap]].<ref name=xxl_interview/><ref name=hhdx/><ref name=observer/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maxim.com/.amp/entertainment/freestyle-fetty-wap-2015-8|last=Iandoli|first=Kathy|title=Fetty Wap Reveals Druggy Origins of Hip-Hop Smash \"Trap Queen\"|date=August 7, 2015|website=[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]|accessdate=September 16, 2018}}</ref> In its lyrics, Wap proclaims his love for his girlfriend, fondly recalling counting [[Federal Reserve Note|money]], going [[shopping]], going to the [[strip club]], getting [[substance intoxication|high]], and \"[[crack cocaine#Chemistry|cooking pies]]\" with her.<ref name=observer/><ref name=guardian/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://genius.com/4592703/Fetty-wap-trap-queen/And-i-get-high-with-my-baby-i-just-left-the-mall-im-gettin-fly-with-my-baby-yeaaahhh-and-i-can-ride-with-my-baby-i-be-in-the-kitchen-cookin-pies-with-my-baby-yeaaahhh-and-i-can-ride-with-my-baby-i-just-left-the-mall-im-gettin-fly-with-my-baby-yeaaahhh-and-i-can-ride-with-my-baby-i-be-in-the-kitchen-cookin-pies-with-my-baby |title=Fetty Wap - Trap Queen Lyrics |website=[[Genius (website)|Genius]] |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref> The lyrics also express an [[hope|aspirational]] quality, with Wap and his girlfriend setting a goal to buy matching [[Lamborghini]]s with the money they earn together. Ural Garrett of [[HipHopDX]] compared the song's lyrical approach to [[urban fiction]] narratives, stating that its themes \"wouldn't feel too out of place in writings from [[Zane (author)|Zane]], [[Wahida Clark]] or Mz. Lady P\".<ref name=hhdx_adventure/>\n\n==Critical reception==\nAlthough some writers called it [[gimmick]]y, \"Trap Queen\" was generally well received by contemporary [[music critics]], especially rap critics.<ref name=guardian/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.villagevoice.com/music/2015/03/nyc_hip_hop_sxsw_2015.php?page=2 |title=A$AP Rocky, Action Bronson, Joey Bada$$ and the Best of NYC Hip-Hop at SXSW 2015 |last=Krishnamurthy |first=Sowmya |work=[[The Village Voice]] |date=March 23, 2015 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref> In particular, multiple writers praised the song's \"[[catchiness|infectious]]\" quality.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2078999/fetty-wap-kanye-west-trap-queen/ |title=Fetty Wap Has Rap's Most Romantic Song Right Now And A Kanye West Co-Sign |last=Markman |first=Rob |website=[[MTV News]] |date=February 13, 2015 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref><ref name=xxl_bestof>{{cite web |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2014/12/14-best-hip-hop-songs-2014/4/ |title=The 14 Best Hip-Hop Songs Of 2014 |work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]] |publisher=[[Townsquare Media]] |date=December 31, 2014 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref> David Drake of ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' highlighted the song for the December 2014 edition of the publication's Bout to Blow feature, calling it a \"sweet, chirpy [[love song]]\" with a \"great chorus and irrepressible cheeriness\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/12/bout-to-blow-december/fetty-wap-trap-queen |title=Bout to Blow: 10 Dope Songs You Should Be Hearing Everywhere Soon |last=Drake |first=David |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=December 1, 2014 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref> Tom Breihan of [[Stereogum]] called it \"one of the best out-of-nowhere rap anthems in recent history\", noting its \"stormy-but-melodic beat\" and \"naggingly catchy [[hook (music)|hook]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stereogum.com/1786649/the-week-in-rap-get-ready-for-skepta-to-be-a-thing/franchises/the-week-in-rap/ |title=The Week In Rap: Get Ready For Skepta To Be A Thing |last=Breihan |first=Tom |website=[[Stereogum]] |date=March 11, 2015 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref> In a particularly positive review for ''[[The Guardian]]'', Ben Westhoff called the song \"a revelation\" that \"sounds simultaneously familiar and exotic\" and ultimately \"succeeds as an oddly touching love story\".<ref name=guardian/> Although Westhoff acknowledged that Wap's singing on \"Trap Queen\" was more compelling than his rapping, he went on to praise Wap's unique voice and singular [[aesthetic]], also lauding the \"dynamic sound\" of Tony Fadd's production. Elliot Pearson of the ''[[Weekly Alibi]]'' called the song an \"[[egalitarianism|egalitarian]] banger dedicated to his partner in crime\" and listed it as a recommended single.<ref name=alibi/>\n\n\"Trap Queen\" was named one of the best songs of 2014 in ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' and ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' magazine's Noisey blog, with the latter publication calling it \"the hottest [[New York City|New York]] record of the year\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/16/best-songs-2014_n_6329526.html |title=The 23 Best Songs Of 2014 |last1=Goodman |first1=Jessica |last2=Kristobak |first2=Ryan |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=December 16, 2014 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://noisey.vice.com/blog/noisey-staff-top-25-songs-of-2014--25-11 |title=Noisey's Top 25 Songs of 2014: 25 to 11 |website=[[Noisey]] |date=December 19, 2014 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref> In addition, it was named one of the best hip hop songs of 2014 in ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]''.<ref name=xxl_bestof/> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' included \"Trap Queen\" in its \"Top 10 Songs of 2015 (So Far)\" list in June 2015, stating \"A hearty \"Hey, what's up, hello\" to one of rap's most uniquely inspired new personalities: Fetty Wap's surprise success story has been all the more enjoyable to witness due to the jubilant debut single on which it is founded. \"Trap Queen\" is teeming with enough hooks and good vibes to have rightfully taken over 2015's first half.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6605615/best-songs-of-2015-so-far-justin-bieber-rihanna-fetty-wap|title=Top 10 Songs of 2015 (So Far)|magazine=Billboard.com}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked \"Trap Queen\" at number 2 on its year-end list to find the 50 best songs of 2015, behind [[The Weeknd]]{{'}}s \"[[Can't Feel My Face]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-best-songs-of-2015-20151203/titus-andronicus-dimed-out-20151203|title=50 Best Songs of 2015|publisher=rollingstone.com}}</ref>\n\n''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' ranked \"Trap Queen\" at number 7 on its year-end list: \"Sure, 'Trap Queen' may have been out since the summer of 2014, but it's impossible to think back on 2015 without acknowledging the overwhelming impact of Fetty Wap, with 'Trap Queen' as his first and best anthem. Whether it's the bouncy nature of Tony Fadd's production, Fetty's insanely catchy hooks or his equally singular [[ad libitum|ad-libs]] (which rang out continuously in clubs and car stereos nationwide), 'Trap Queen' captured attention on its way to a No. 2 peak on the Hot 100, creating a new superstar along the way.\" <ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/year-in-music-2015/6806155/billboard-25-best-songs-critics-picks|title=Billboard 25 Best Songs of 2015: Critics' Picks|magazine=Billboard.com}}</ref> The ''[[Village Voice]]'' named \"Trap Queen\" the seventh-best single released in 2015 on their annual year-end critics' poll, [[Pazz & Jop]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://furia.com/pjs/table_song_2015_total.html|title=Pazz & Jop Statistics|newspaper=The Village Voice|accessdate=January 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\nFollowing its December 2014 re-release, \"Trap Queen\" became Fetty Wap's nationwide breakthrough and the first major hit single for 300 Entertainment.<ref name=insidethesuccess>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6524215/inside-fetty-wap-trap-queen-lyor-cohen-300 |title=Inside the Success of Fetty Wap's 'Trap Queen,' the First Hit for Lyor Cohen's 300 Entertainment |last1=Hampp |first1=Andrew |last2=Mitchell |first2=Gail |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref> It debuted on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 at number 86 for the chart dated February 7, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-02-07 |title=The Hot 100: The Week of February 7, 2015 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref> The song entered the chart's top ten seven weeks later, largely on the strength of its [[streaming media|streaming]] activity and digital download sales.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-03-28 |title=The Hot 100: Week of March 28, 2015 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6502503/mark-ronson-bruno-mars-hot-100-sam-smith-fetty-wap |title=Mark Ronson, Bruno Mars Lead Hot 100; Sam Smith, Fetty Wap Hit Top 10 |last=Trust |first=Gary |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=March 18, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref> It peaked at number two for three consecutive weeks beginning on the chart dated May 16, 2015, held from the top spot by [[Wiz Khalifa]]'s \"[[See You Again (Wiz Khalifa song)|See You Again]]\" featuring [[Charlie Puth]].<ref>\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-05-16 |title=The Hot 100: The Week of May 16, 2015 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |accessdate=May 21, 2015}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-05-23 |title=The Hot 100: The Week of May 23, 2015 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |accessdate=May 21, 2015}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-05-30 |title=The Hot 100: The Week of May 30, 2015 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |accessdate=May 21, 2015}}</ref> Over the course of its run, \"Trap Queen\" had also reached number one on [[Hot Rap Songs]] and number two on [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]], rising to its peak on the latter chart concurrently with taking over the number one position on [[R&B/Hip-Hop Airplay]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6516507/fetty-waps-trap-queen-tops-hot-rap-songs-chart |title=Fetty Wap's 'Trap Queen' Tops Hot Rap Songs Chart |last=Mendizabal |first=Amaya |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=March 26, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6523917/weeknd-first-number-1-hot-rb-hip-hop |title=The Weeknd Earns First No. 1 on Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs |last=Mendizabal |first=Amaya |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=April 2, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref> By the end of 2015, \"Trap Queen\" had sold 2,730,000 digital downloads domestically.<ref name=us_sales>{{cite web | url=http://www.nielsen.com/content/dam/corporate/us/en/reports-downloads/2016-reports/2015-year-end-music-report.pdf.pdf | title=2015 Nielsen Music U.S. Report | publisher=Nielsen | date=January 6, 2016 | accessdate=January 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n\"Trap Queen\u201d generated the most on-demand streams in 2015, according to Nielsen Music, with a combined total of 616.46 million audio and video streams. It was one of five songs to surpass 400 million in on-demand streams during the year.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6835354/us-on-demand-music-streams-increase | title=U.S. On-Demand Music Streams Increase 93% in 2015, With Fetty Wap Leading the Way | work=Billboard | date=January 6, 2016 | accessdate=January 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] for \"Trap Queen\", directed by RGF Productions head Nitt Da Gritt, was uploaded to Fetty Wap's [[YouTube]] channel on August 7, 2014 and has received more than 620 million views as of January 2019.<ref name=boombox/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://freeonsmash.com/music/fetty-wap-trap-queen/ |title=Fetty Wap \u2013 Trap Queen |author=Jay the Pusha |website=[[OnSMASH]] |date=November 20, 2014 |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref name=musicvideo>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i_kF4zLNKio |title=Fetty Wap - Trap Queen (Official Video) Prod. By Tony Fadd |website=[[YouTube]] |date=August 7, 2014 |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref> Set in Wap's home neighborhood in Paterson, New Jersey,<ref name=hhdx_adventure>{{cite web |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/editorials/id.2802/title.fetty-waps-california-adventure |title=Fetty Wap's California Adventure |last=Garrett |first=Ural |website=[[HipHopDX]] |publisher=Cheri Media Group |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref> the video depicts Wap and his onscreen girlfriend at their apartment and amidst a group of neighbors partying. Wap first arrives to his home in a black [[BMW]] [[convertible]],<ref name=hhdx_adventure/> where he is greeted by his girlfriend and joins her inside, where many others are gathered. The two are shown counting money and [[smoking]] together, and one shot shows Wap's girlfriend [[baking]] a [[pie]]. Later, Wap's girlfriend drives a white car to meet Wap on a street at his black convertible, where Wap kisses her and hands her a stack of dollar bills before they walk away together. The remainder of the video shows Wap socializing with neighbors at an outdoor gathering. The video is interspersed with shots of Wap outdoors singing the song while a crowd of neighbors dances and sings along behind him.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nWesthoff of ''The Guardian'' speculated that the video was filmed on a limited [[budget]], but conceded that it had \"a strong [[cin\u00e9ma v\u00e9rit\u00e9|v\u00e9rit\u00e9]] quality to it\" as a result. He likened the video to a less cinematic version of [[Juvenile (rapper)|Juvenile]]'s music video for \"[[Ha (song)|Ha]]\".<ref name=guardian>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/mar/25/fetty-wap-trap-queen-new-jersey-rap-hip-hop |title=Fetty Wap: New Jersey's trap king vies for rap throne with Trap Queen |last=Westhoff |first=Ben |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=Guardian News & Media |date=March 25, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, the video earned [[Music Choice]]'s first MC100 Award of 2015 for being the service's most-played video of the year up to that point. It was Wap's first award.<ref>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7wALJLNz9NQ |title=Fetty Wap Receives His First Award Ever from Music Choice! |publisher=[[Music Choice]] |via=[[YouTube]] |date=June 10, 2015 |accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\n\"Trap Queen\" received much of its early attention through social media websites like Twitter and Instagram, where Fetty Wap and his team had directed early promotional efforts for the song.<ref name=observer/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/rising/9640-fetty-wap-too-many-hooks/ |title=Fetty Wap: Too Many Hooks |last=Goble |first=Corban |website=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] |date=May 1, 2015 |accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref> A major early source of exposure through such media was the rapper [[Bobby Shmurda]] \u2014 at the time enjoying the success of his own [[viral video|viral]] hit single \"[[Hot Nigga]]\" \u2014 who posted a video to his Instagram account on October 16, 2014 in which he sang along to \"Trap Queen\".<ref name=8things/> \"Every girl wants to be a trap queen now, but how you gonna cook [[crack cocaine|crack]] when you can't even cook [[breakfast]]?\" would eventually become a popular social media [[Internet meme|meme]] inspired by the song.<ref name=guardian/>\n\nToward the end of 2014 and early in 2015, the promotional focus for Wap and his team shifted toward performing [[concert|live]] and securing mainstream [[airplay]]. By November 2014, the song had begun amassing airplay within the [[New York metropolitan area|tri-state area]] from stations like [[WQHT|Hot 97]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/11/fetty-wap-trap-queen-interview |title=Interview: Fetty Wap Talks \"Trap Queen,\" His Eye, and What's Next |last=Diaz |first=Angel |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=November 20, 2014 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref> in particular, 300 Entertainment co-founder [[Todd Moscowitz]] credited that station's [[Funkmaster Flex]] as an important early champion of the song at radio.<ref name=insidethesuccess/> On February 12, 2015, rap superstar [[Kanye West]] brought Wap onstage as a surprise guest at the first annual Roc City Classic concert hosted by [[Roc Nation]] and [[Power 105.1]] in [[Madison Square Park]]. West proclaimed \"Trap Queen\" his \"favorite song\" of the moment, and [[Jay Z]] and [[Beyonc\u00e9]] were seen dancing in the audience together as Wap performed the song.<ref name=8things/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6472741/kanye-west-headlines-roc-city-classic-travis-scott-fetty-wap |title=Kanye West Headlines Roc City Classic with Travi$ Scott, Fetty Wap & More |last=Williams |first=Nick |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=February 13, 2015 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref> Wap also performed the song at his own shows, including a showcase at [[South by Southwest]],<ref name=sxsw/><ref name=insidethesuccess/> along with further guest performances at shows for [[Chris Brown]] and [[Trey Songz]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6473073/chris-brown-trey-songz-barclays-concert-review |title=Chris Brown & Trey Songz Bring 'Between the Sheets' Show to Brooklyn: Live Review |last=Platon |first=Adelle |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=February 17, 2015 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/entertainment/music-news-reviews/article14490548.html |title=Concert review: Chris Brown lives up to his reputation |last=Arriero |first=Elisabeth |work=[[The Charlotte Observer]] |date=March 15, 2015 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vibe.com/2015/06/chris-brown-one-hell-of-a-night-tour/ |title=Chris Brown Announces 'One Hell Of A Night' Tour |last=Golding |first=Shenequa |work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]] |publisher=[[SpinMedia]] |date=June 8, 2015 |accessdate=June 10, 2015}}</ref> \"Trap Queen\" was also the final song performed in Wap's closing set at the 2015 [[XXL (magazine)#XXL Freshmen|''XXL'' Freshmen]] show.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/review/6613233/fetty-wap-2015-xxl-freshmen-nyc-show-live-review |title=Fetty Wap Dominates Lukewarm 2015 XXL Freshmen NYC Show: Live Review |last=Diep |first=Eric |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=July 1, 2015 |accessdate=July 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn his [[television]] debut, Wap performed \"Trap Queen\" at the [[2015 MTV Movie Awards]] with [[Fall Out Boy]] on April 12, 2015. The band opened the performance with part of their own hit single \"[[Centuries (song)|Centuries]]\" before [[segue]]ing into Wap's performance of \"Trap Queen\", for which they provided instrumental and backing vocal accompaniment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2131214/fall-out-boy-fetty-wap-mtv-movie-awards-performance/ |title=Watch Fall Out Boy Give Fetty Wap's 'Trap Queen' The Rock Star Treatment |last=Lindner |first=Emilee |website=[[MTV News]] |date=April 12, 2015 |accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref> Wap also performed the song as a musical guest on two [[late-night talk show]]s: first on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'' May 5, accompanied by [[The Roots]], then on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' June 9, accompanied by [[Brooklyn]] band [[Phony Ppl]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2153063/fetty-wap-trap-queen-jimmy-fallon/ |title=Thanks To Fetty Wap, Jimmy Fallon Now Knows What A 'Trap Queen' Is |last=Alexis |first=Nadeska |website=[[MTV News]] |date=May 6, 2015 |accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spin.com/2015/06/fetty-wap-trap-queen-my-way-jimmy-kimmel/ |title=Fetty Wap Plays 'Trap Queen' and 'My Way' With Full Band on 'Kimmel' |last=Unterberger |first=Andrew |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |publisher=[[SpinMedia]] |date=June 10, 2015 |accessdate=June 10, 2015}}</ref> He also performed the song as a guest on ''[[Nick Cannon Presents Wild 'n Out]]'' June 24 and as the closing performer on the [[BET Awards 2015]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/shows/nick_cannon_wildnout/trap-queen-live/1205423/video/ |title=Trap Queen (Live) |website=[[MTV]] |date=June 24, 2015 |accessdate=July 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/nick-cannon-presents-wild-n-out/pete-wentz-fetty-wap-3081005/ |title=Nick Cannon Presents Wild 'N Out - Season 7, Episode 4: Pete Wentz, Fetty Wap |website=[[TV.com]] |accessdate=July 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rap-up.com/2015/06/28/video-fetty-wap-performs-trap-queen-at-bet-awards/ |title=Fetty Wap Performs at BET Awards |website=Rap-Up |date=June 28, 2015 |accessdate=July 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Remixes===\nSeveral unofficial [[remix]]es and freestyles of \"Trap Queen\" were released by other artists as the song became more popular. Artists releasing their takes and guest verses on the song included [[French Montana]], [[Fabolous]], [[Rick Ross]] and [[Fat Trel]], [[Yo Gotti]], [[Quavo]], [[Lil' Kim]], [[Shy Glizzy]] and [[Da Brat]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2015/02/8-remixes-fetty-waps-hit-single-trap-queen/ |title=8 Remixes of Fetty Wap's Hit Single 'Trap Queen' |last=Krastz |first=Roger |work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]] |publisher=[[Townsquare Media]] |date=February 26, 2015 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/new-music/2015/03/rick-ross-fat-trel-remix-fetty-waps-trap-queen/ |title=Rick Ross and Fat Trel Remix Fetty Wap's 'Trap Queen' |last=Coleman |first= C. Vernon |work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]] |publisher=[[Townsquare Media]] |date=March 7, 2015 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref> In particular, Wap favored Quavo's verse,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/ontheverge/2015/03/15/fetty-wap-trap-queen-on-the-verge/24456943/ |title=On the Verge: Fetty Wap crowns a 'Trap Queen' |last=Mansfield |first=Brian |authorlink=Brian Mansfield |work=[[USA Today]] |publisher=[[Gannett Company]] |date=March 15, 2015 |accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref> which was later incorporated into the song's official remix, also featuring a verse from Gucci Mane, Wap's favorite rapper.<ref name=remix_premiere>{{cite web |url=https://www.thefader.com/2015/05/05/fetty-wap-trap-queen-remix-gucci-mane-quavo |title=Fetty Wap Shares \"Trap Queen\" Remix With Gucci Mane And Quavo |last=Zeichner |first=Naomi |work=[[The Fader]] |date=May 5, 2015 |accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref> The remix was released commercially on May 4, 2015 in the United States,<ref name=remix>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/trap-queen-feat.-quavo-gucci/id991383022 |title=Trap Queen (feat. Quavo & Gucci Mane) - Single by Fetty Wap |website=[[iTunes]] |date=May 4, 2015 |accessdate=May 6, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150506225510/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/trap-queen-feat.-quavo-gucci/id991383022 |archivedate=May 6, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> while an international version featuring an additional verse from [[Azealia Banks]] was released on the same day in other territories.<ref name=remix_premiere/><ref name=azealia_remix>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/trap-queen-feat.-azealia-banks/id991383746 |title=Trap Queen (feat. Azealia Banks, Quavo, Gucci Mane) - Single by Fetty Wap |website=[[iTunes]] |date=May 4, 2015 |accessdate=May 6, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150506225602/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/trap-queen-feat.-azealia-banks/id991383746 |archivedate=May 6, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> In late May 2015, it was reported that a remix featuring [[Nigeria]]n artists [[Wizkid (musician)|Wizkid]], [[Davido]] and [[Ice Prince]] would be released.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Fetty Wap To Feature Davido, Wizkid & Ice Prince on Trap Queen (Afro Remix)|website = Reports Afrique|url = http://reportsafrique.com/2015/05/fetty-wap-to-feature-davido-wizkid-ice-prince-on-trap-queen-afroremix/|date = May 26, 2015|accessdate = June 5, 2015b|last = Chukwu|first = Victor|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150601154437/http://reportsafrique.com/2015/05/fetty-wap-to-feature-davido-wizkid-ice-prince-on-trap-queen-afroremix/#|archive-date = 2015-06-01|url-status = dead}}</ref> In 2015, a version was done by British musician and narrator [[George the Poet]] which included mentioning the song's subject and meaning, and frustration with British politics.<ref>{{cite web |title=George The Poet - Trap Queen (Fetty Wap's cover in the Live Lounge) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q6suJjSI_Tw |website=www.youtube.com |accessdate=8 August 2018 |date=17 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2015)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|25|artist=Fetty Wap|song=Trap Queen|accessdate=August 8, 2015|rowheader=true}}\n|- \n{{singlechart|Flanders Tip|4|artist=Fetty Wap|song=Trap Queen|accessdate=June 19, 2015|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia Tip|18|artist=Fetty Wap|song=Trap Queen|accessdate=July 3, 2015|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders Urban|19|artist=Fetty Wap|song=Trap Queen|accessdate=July 3, 2015|rowheader=true}}<!-- stop deleting this entry w/o explanation; ESPECIALLY since this is the only Ultratop (i.e. non-UltraTIP) chart the song has reached, this peak position is NOT needless/redundant!! -->\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcanadianhot100|11|artist=Fetty Wap|accessdate=June 25, 2015|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Canada [[Canada CHR/Top 40|CHR/Top 40]] ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref>{{cite web|title=Chart Search|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/search/charts?f%5b0%5d=ts_chart_artistname%3AFetty%20Wap&f%5b1%5d=itm_field_chart_id%3A1239&f%5b2%5d=ss_bb_type%3Achart_item&type=2&artist=Fetty%20Wap|publisher=[[Billboard charts|Billboard]] [[Canada CHR/Top 40]] for Fetty Wap|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref>\n| 49\n|-\n{{singlechart|Denmark|8|artist=Fetty Wap|song=Trap Queen|accessdate=June 12, 2015|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|17|artist=Fetty Wap|song=Trap Queen|accessdate=July 12, 2015|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Germany ([[GfK Entertainment|Official German Charts]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/titel